<HEADLINE> Vietnam to Boost Economic Relations with U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's Deputy Prime Minister
Nguyen Tan Dung met visiting U.S. Deputy Secretary of Commerce
Robert Mallett here Tuesday, saying Vietnam wants further
cooperation and sincere assistance in investment and trade from
other countries, including the United States.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Deputy Secretary Mallett arrived here Tuesday for an
official visit at the invitation of Trade Minister Vu Khoan.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the Vietnamese Deputy Prime Minister said
that the sole objective of Vietnamese government is to
comprehensively develop the national economy and accelerate the
economic renovation process.
</P>
<P>
Dung and Mallett shared the view that the two countries should
boost bilateral ties in investment and commerce while waiting for
approval of the trade agreement by the parliaments of the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese Deputy Prime Minister also welcomed U.S.
readiness to provide technical assistance to Vietnam in trade and
to support Vietnam's joining the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
Mallett said the signing of the U.S.-Vietnam Trade Agreement
had created a new framework for the two sides' cooperation in most
fields.
</P>
<P>
He also affirmed the desire of U.S. businesses to cooperate
with Vietnamese partners in boosting trade and investment
operations.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Deputy Secretary Mallett is scheduled to end his visit on
Thursday. Vietnam is the second stop of Mallett's visit to East
Asia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
