<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Nepal Strives to Improve People's Health by Zhuang Meijie, Song Dejun </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 22 (Xinhua) -- A program was launched in
Nepal Monday by some internal and international non-governmental
organizations to raise the awareness of sanitation among people
and prioritize the environmental sanitation issues in the nation's
development agenda.
</P>
<P>
The objective of the program is to "make people understand the
basic hygienic ways of living and bring sanitation and hygiene in
national advocacy through media reporting," said Wing-Sie Cheng,
chief of communications at UNICEF (U.N. Children's Fund), one of
the organizers of the program.
</P>
<P>
Sanitation situation is presenting an ever grimmer picture in
Nepal. Statistics show that Nepalese spend 10 billion rupees (140
million U.S. dollars) annually to cure diseases due to lack of
sanitation and clean drinking water.
</P>
<P>
Although the Nepali government spent 300 million dollars in
recent years on sanitation projects, the situation is not so
encouraging yet.
</P>
<P>
Data presented by Dr. Sarad Onta at a consultative meeting for
the program held on Monday shows that the infant mortality rate in
Nepal is 80 deaths every 1,000 births, 125 babies among 1,000
under five years old die of cholera and around 35,000 children
aged under five die every year due to diarrhea.
</P>
<P>
The data also reveals that 40 percent of the people suffer from
various diseases due to unhygienic living conditions.
</P>
<P>
Besides poor sanitation and unclean drinking water, unhygienic
behavior and ways of living are also the factor leading to the
wide prevalence of contagious diseases in Nepal.
</P>
<P>
"We are facing problems in making people realize the importance
of clean sanitary habits," said Mohan Bhatta, an official with the
Public Health Department.
</P>
<P>
For many Nepalese, especially those in rural areas, abandoning
their age-old habits of searching for "a corner behind the bushes"
nearby is easier and more acceptable than going to the newly-
constructed toilet. About 80 percent of rural families do not have
a toilet of their own.
</P>
<P>
The practice of keeping menstruating women and those on labor
in the cowsheds is still widely practiced in rural areas due to
superstitious thinking.
</P>
<P>
Realizing the seriousness of the sanitation problem, the Nepali
government has set the target of making clean drinking water
available to all people and sanitation available to 40 percent of
the population.
</P>
<P>
However, given the present availability of drinking water and
sanitation to 61 percent and 20 percent of the total population,
experts fear that the target is too ambitious. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
