<HEADLINE> Liberia Refuses to Grant Bail to Journalists on Spy Charge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 22 (Xinhua) -- A Liberian court Tuesday turned
down a request to grant bail to four foreign journalists on spying
charges.
</P>
<P>
"Under Liberian law, espionage is a first degree felony and
there can be no bail," Judge Timothy Swope was quoted as saying in
the west African nation's capital Monrovia.
</P>
<P>
Gugu Radebe, a freelance South African cameraman, Timothy
Lambon, who holds dual British and South African citizenship,
Sierra Leonean producer Samura Sorious and Briton David Barrie
were arrested in Monrovia last Friday on suspicion of espionage
while filming a three-part documentary for the British television
station Channel 4.
</P>
<P>
Liberia's Justice Department has accused them of engaging in "
clandestine activity to injure the image and character of the
president of Liberia".
</P>
<P>
The case has drawn an angry reaction from Britain. The British
Foreign Office minister for African affairs Peter Hain warned
Liberia Tuesday that the men's detention had put it on a collision
course with the international community and called for their
immediate release.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the U.S. special envoy to Africa Jesse Jackson has
reportedly appealed to President Charles Taylor to release the
four men.
</P>
<P>
According to Jackson, Taylor promised to give his request "his
highest consideration" but only after the journalists appear
before a magistrate court.
</P>
<P>
If convicted, the four, who arrived in the country on August 1
and were charged on Monday, could face up to 10 years in jail,
according to reports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
