<DOCNO> XIE20000823.0006 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Traffic Accidents Pose Grave Threat to Jordanian Society </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The alarming rate of traffic
accidents in Jordan has posed a serious social and economic threat
to the kingdom as the accidents claimed hundreds of lives and
millions of U.S. dollars in economic losses each year, a senior
police officer said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
At a seminar held in the northern town of Irbid, Deputy Director
of the Public Security Department Abdul Salem Garfira said 676
people were killed and 19,015 people injured in road accidents in
1999 alone, with a total estimated economic loss of some 200
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Some 11,000 people have been killed and 250,000 others injured
in nearly half a million traffic accidents in the desert kingdom,
he added.
</P>
<P>
Most of the accidents took place in the capital Amman or its
surrounding areas, which are home to one third of the country's 4.7
million population, he said.
</P>
<P>
From 1994 to 1999, the kingdom has witnessed a 13 percent growth
in its traffic accidents and a 8 percent growth rate in traffic-
related casualties annually, he said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the traffic safety of Jordan is far below
international standards, and the death rate among each 10,000
vehicles stands at 16, or 10 times higher than that of developed
countries.
</P>
<P>
Traffic authorities are launching education campaigns among
drivers, and imposing tougher traffic laws to curb the rising road
accidents across the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Under a new law, the maximum fine could be up to 1,000 Jordanian
dinars (1,400 dollars) on hit-and-run drivers, or drivers who are
transporting hazardous materials or explosives without proper
authorization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
