<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The following are the economic
briefs from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Cartier International is expected to open its
Middle East office in Dubai towards the end of October.
</P>
<P>
A warehouse and a regional after-sales centre will be set up at
the Dubai Airport Free Zone, said Philippe McGarry, managing
director of Vendome (Dubai), holder of Cartier International and
other brands.
</P>
<P>
Last April, Cartier started dealing directly with retail
customers and sent a delegation to the region to analyse the
market.
</P>
<P>
Another team visited the Middle East in June to finalize the
commercial audit of regional operations and look at retaining or
closing down some points-of-sale.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- There are big savings in store for the United Arab
Emirates travellers as major airlines here are poised to slash
fares and offer bonanza packages in a bid to fill seats during the
annual slack period which starts early next month.
</P>
<P>
Major airlines flying to the United States, Europe, and East
Asia will cut their fares, and some are also developing special
packages and incentives to lure more passengers during the off-peak
season.
</P>
<P>
Travel agency sources in Abu Dhabi said most of the airlines
would maintain their low fares as an incentive to attract
passengers until March 31 next year to cover the period following
the traditional peak travelling season in the emirates.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Studies at the Al Lootah International University
For Internet will begin from the new academic year next month, Haj
Saeed bin Ahmed Al Lootah, president of the University's Supreme
Council was quoted on Wednesday by local media.
</P>
<P>
He stated that all information about the University will be
available at the web site: www.lootah.sch.ae.
</P>
<P>
The University will offer two programmes, master's and doctoral
degrees in Economics and Commerce, Islamic Banking, Management and
Leadership, Accounting and Computer Science and Information
Systems.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The size of the UAE's information technology market
could cross the 2-billion-dirham (546.4 million U.S. dollars) mark
for the first time this year, nearly 20 percent over 1999's 1.68
billion dirhams (459 million dollars), according to International
Data Corp. (IDC) estimates.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- A senior Iranian official stressed on Wednesday that
the country should make more investments in tourism to increase
government revenues.
</P>
<P>
Iran is among the top 10 tourist sites in the world, but
significant domestic investments are needed to fetch good revenues
in this sector, said Deputy Interior Minister for Development
Affairs Ahmad Khorram. 
</P>
</TEXT>
