<DOCNO> XIE20000823.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandate of U.N. Mission in Congo Extended </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In a resolution adopted after informal consultations, the
Council said the "technical extension" can also allow the Council
more time to think about the mission's future mandate and "
possible adjustments".
</P>
<P>
The mandate of the mission, known as MONUC, is set to expire on
August 31 according to the February 24 Council resolution, which
requests U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan to present his next
report on the latest developments in the Central African country
by August 24.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the Council released here a week ago, the U.N.
chief requested an interim extension of the mission through
September 30 to allow sufficient time to assess the impact of the
latest developments and to formulate recommendations.
</P>
<P>
The "adverse climate" in the DRC has so far prevented the
deployment of MONUC in accordance with relevant Council
resolutions, said Annan, calling attention to the persistent large-
scale fighting in many parts of the country, formerly known as
Zaire.
</P>
<P>
He also noted the severe restrictions imposed by the DRC
authorities and other parties on MONUC's freedom of movement.
</P>
<P>
The Lusaka peace process, which started in 1999 to end the two-
year civil war which has claimed 1.7 million lives, is undergoing
"an extremely challenging phase" and requires substantial re-
evaluation by its signatories and the United Nations, Annan said.
</P>
<P>
The Council agreed in February to send 500 cease-fire observers
and 5,500 troops to protect them. But the plan has been put on
hold because Kinshasa barred them from entering the area under the
government control.
</P>
<P>
The latest resolution requests Annan to report to the Council
by September 21 on progress in implementing the cease-fire
agreement and make recommendations for further Council action.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000823.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Czech Government Approves Referendum Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The Czech government approved a
constitutional bill on referenda Wednesday to allow citizens
directly decide on the especially important issues concerning the
country's policies, the Czech News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Under the bill, a referendum can be held to decide on
fundamental internal or foreign policy issues of the country.
</P>
<P>
The bill stipulates that a proposal for calling a referendum
can be submitted to the president by any of the two parliamentary
houses, by the government or by citizens in a petition signed by
at least 300,000 people.
</P>
<P>
The bill also says that referenda contradicting with the
constitutionally guaranteed rights and freedoms or the country's
international commitments are invalid.
</P>
<P>
The bill awaits ratification by both houses of the parliament.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000823.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania, Slovenia FMs hold talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Romanian Foreign Minister
Petre Roman Wednesday met at Neptune resort of Black Sea shore
with his visiting Slovenian counterpart Alojz Peterle, and they
discussed the cooperation opportunities between the two countries,
in the perspective of their EU and NATO joining.
</P>
<P>
"We discussed, during the meeting, the opportunities to develop
the project of a Constanta-Trieste oil and gas pipeline cross
Romania, Hungary, Croatia, Slovenia and Italy," the Romanian chief
diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
The bilateral cooperation also develops within the South-
Eastern European Stability Pact, and above all within the
Initiative for Cooperation in South-East Europe (SECI), whose
presidentship Romania enjoys, Petre Roman said, adding that
Slovenia will also participate in the works with the Bucharest-
based SECI center for fighting organized crime.
</P>
<P>
Likewise, Romania and Slovenia have negotiated and are to sign
several accords on fighting organized crime, readmission,
transport and customs, Petre Roman noted.
</P>
<P>
Alojz Peterle, who arrived here on Wednesday for a one-day
visit, said in his turn that he was pleased with the steady manner
the Romanian Slovenian relations had been developing. The talks
focused the bilateral cooperation in the field of tourism, and the
Slovenian companies were encouraged to vie with the Romanian ones,
the Slovenian dignitary said. At the same time, Alojz Peterle
declared himself content with the fact that Romania and Slovenia
share the same views and goals aiming at EU and NATO integration.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
