<HEADLINE> Romania, Slovenia to Develop Bilateral Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Romanian Foreign Minister
Petre Roman Wednesday met at the Neptune resort of the Black Sea
shore with his Slovenian counterpart, Alojz Peterle, to discuss
the opportunities of cooperation between the two countries in the
perspective of their joining into the EU and NATO.
</P>
<P>
"We discussed, during the meeting, the opportunities to develop
the project of a Constanta-Trieste oil and gas pipeline cross
Romania, Hungary, Croatia, Slovenia and Italy," the Romanian chief
diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
The bilateral cooperation also develops within the South-
Eastern European Stability Pact, and above all within the
Initiative for Cooperation in South-East Europe (SECI), whose
presidentship Romania enjoys, Petre Roman said, adding that
Slovenia will also participate in the work with the Bucharest-
based SECI center for fighting organized crime.
</P>
<P>
Likewise, Romania and Slovenia have negotiated and are to sign
several accords on fighting organized crime, readmission,
transport and customs, Petre Roman said.
</P>
<P>
Alojz Peterle, who arrived here Wednesday for a one-day visit,
said in his turn that he was pleased with the steady manner the
Romanian-Slovenian relations had been developing. The talks
focused on the bilateral cooperation in the field of tourism, and
the Slovenian companies were encouraged to vie with the Romanian
ones, the Slovenian dignitary said. At the same time, Alojz
Peterle declared himself content with the fact that Romania and
Slovenia share the views and goals aiming at EU and NATO
integration. 
