<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges OPEC to Increase Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 23 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Wednesday urged the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
(OPEC) to increase production and cautioned that OPEC would suffer
if costly oil caused recession among consuming countries.
</P>
<P>
"I'm going to... continue to argue to all the OPEC nations that
if the price gets too high, they will cause recession in other
countries and then the supply -- the purchases will drop
dramatically and for a longer period of time," the president said
at a press conference at the White House.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said that he would be happier with oil prices in the
range of 20-25 U.S. dollars a barrel.
</P>
<P>
"The low- to mid-20s is a more sustainable rate," he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he would discuss the issue during his upcoming
meetings with Nigerian President Obasanjo and with leaders of
other oil-producing countries. Nigeria is a member of OPEC.
</P>
<P>
Oil prices surged again Wednesday as dealers reacted sharply to
news of an unexpected decline in inventories held by the United
States, the world's largest oil importer.
</P>
<P>
The American Petroleum Institute said Tuesday that U.S. crude
stocks in the week to August 18 down 7.7 million barrels at 279.7
million, 11 percent down on the same time last year and near a 24-
year low.
</P>
<P>
Oil has risen sharply from a 22-year low of less than 10
dollars a barrel in 1998 after a series of OPEC supply curbs which
the cartel has partially lifted this year.
</P>
<P>
OPEC ministers are expected to raise production by at least 500,
000 barrels daily when they meet on September 10 in Vienna.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000823.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Expresses Support for Mexican President-Elect Fox </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 23 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton said
on Wednesday that he would reaffirm U.S. strong support to close
ties with Mexico when he meet Mexican president-elect Vicente Fox
this week.
</P>
<P>
"I want to reaffirm the support of the United States, which I
think is bipartisan, for good strong relationships with Mexico,"
Clinton told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Fox, who won a presidential election on July 2 and will take
office on December 1, will arrive Washington on Thursday after his
visit to Canada.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he wanted to discuss with Fox the two countries'
efforts to deal with the problem of illegal drugs, common
environmental issues along the border, and how to make the U.S.-
Mexican trade relationship work for both sides.
</P>
<P>
"I think he's quite serious about modernizing the Mexican
economy and moving forward with our relationship," he said.
</P>
<P>
When asked about Fox's proposal to expand North American Free
Trade Agreement (NAFTA) into a body like the European Union,
Clinton said he wanted to hear what Fox would have to say.
</P>
<P>
"In general, I think there will be increasing interdependence
of the world's economies over the next decade, increasing
interdependence in our region," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I didn't extend our trade agreements to the rest of South
America, and I think that the Europeans have benefited at our
expense," Clinton said. "So I think there will be more
interdependence and the United States has to be a part of that."
</P>
<P>
Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien, who met with Fox in
Ottawa on Tuesday, expressed little enthusiasm for Fox's proposal,
saying he thought that NAFTA was going very well and did not think
that one could apply European-style rules to the agreement.
</P>
</TEXT>
