<HEADLINE> Security Council Urges Afghan Parties to Resume Talks Without Delay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Security Council Wednesday urged Afghan parties, in particular the
Taliban, to stop fighting and resume the negotiations under the
United Nations auspices without further delay and preconditions.
</P>
<P>
The move came after the 15-member Security Council was briefed
by the Secretariat on the latest situation in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Expressing its grave concern over the continued armed conflict
in the country, the Security Council reiterated its call to all
Afghan parties to work together for peace and the establishment of
a broad-based multiethnic and fully representative government.
</P>
<P>
The council expressed its deep concern over further
deterioration of the humanitarian and human rights situation in
the country and insisted that all parties take responsibility for
the safety and the security of the civilian population and of
humanitarian personnel.
</P>
<P>
The council condemned the recent killing of seven de-mining
workers working under the auspices of the United Nations mine-
clearing program and called on the Taliban authorities to bring
the perpetrators to justice.
</P>
<P>
The council reiterated that continuing disregard by the Taliban
of the demands made in its relevant resolutions was totally
unacceptable, and confirmed its determination to ensure full
compliance by the Taliban without conditions with its obligations
under relevant U.N. resolutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
