<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Suspends Aid Operations in West Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The move followed "the worst attack" against the agency's
personnel working in West Timor with three UNHCR staffers
suffering severe injuries, spokesman Fred Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
The incident took place Tuesday night while the three were
distributing plastic sheeting at a refugee camp 130 km east of the
provincial capital of Kupang. They were beaten up by local militia
armed with machetes, clubs and stones, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Indonesian Army officials in the area failed to respond
immediately to the incident, considered by UNHCR as the worst of
more than 100 recorded cases of harassment and intimidation
against aid workers and refugees since last September," Eckhard
added.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday Indonesian authorities told the U.N. Traditional
Administration in East Timor (UNTAET) that the refugee camps in
West Timor will be closed down within three to six months in
coordination with the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The UNTAET welcomed the initiative to expedite voluntary
repatriation or resettlement of the refugees still in West Timor,
according to Eckhard.
</P>
<P>
There are an estimated 85,000 to 120,000 East Timor refugees,
who fled or were forced by pro-Indonesia militia to flee to West
Timor when violence erupted in East Timor after its people voted
overwhelmingly for independence in August 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
