<HEADLINE> Gulf Air Plane Crashes Near Bahrain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAMA, August 23 (Xinhua) -- A Gulf Air plane on a schedule
flight to Egyptian capital Cairo from Bahrain crashed Wednesday in
the waters of the Persian Gulf near Bahrain, a Bahraini official
said.
</P>
<P>
The Airbus A320 carrying 140 people plunged into the waters
shortly after taking off from the Bahraini International Airport in
the country's capital of Manama, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Witness reported a fire in one of the engines of the flight
GF072. The rescue operation is underway in the waters and
helicopters of Bahraini coast guard are involved.
</P>
<P>
No news available if there are surviors found in the waters.
</P>
<P>
Gulf Air belongs in equal parts to Bahrain, Oman, Qatar and the
government of Abu Dhabi, the largest of seven sheikdoms making up
the United Arab Emirates. The Bahrain-based Gulf Air operates a
fleet of 28 planes and flies to 53 international destinations.
</P>
