<HEADLINE> Much to be Done to Curb HIV/AIDS in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Much has to be done to curb the
spread of HIV/AIDS pandemic in Africa, a red cross official said
here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Holger Liepe, head of a delegation in Zambia from the
International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies (
IFRCS), told the Zambia Red Cross HIV/AIDS youth initiative
campaign that HIV/AIDS is the biggest threat in many countries and
has retarded development in the region.
</P>
<P>
Liepe attributed the rapid spread of the disease to the lack of
seriousness and financial constraints.
</P>
<P>
He added that changing the behavior of fellow citizens should
be of first priority if the initiative was to be a success.
</P>
<P>
He urged the youths and volunteers to teach the people the
importance of using condoms and that they should stay faithful to
one partner in order to halt the spread of the disease.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the same function, Zambia Red Cross Society youth
advisor Joel Oyo said the organization would make sure the
initiative was taken to the furthest point in the country since it
had the largest number of youth volunteers placed around the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
