<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean War Veterans Protest at President Office </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's war veterans held
demonstration outside President Robert Mugabe's office here
Wednesday, demanding an explanation on why police destroyed their
properties.
</P>
<P>
According to the Zimbabwe News Agency, Home Affairs Minister
John Nkomo last week had instructed police to evict war veterans
from the white-owned farms and private land they had occupied by
burning and destroying their houses.
</P>
<P>
"John Nkomo has sold out. Down with him," said one of the many
messages inscribed on placards waved by the former liberation
fighters outside Mugabe's office.
</P>
<P>
Although the war veterans went to Mugabe's office in the
morning, they had not met the president by lunch time. Mugabe was
said to be attending a Cabinet meeting in the same building.
</P>
<P>
Neither war veterans leader Chenjerai Hunzvi nor commander-in-
chief of the farm invasions Joseph Chinotimba could be reached for
comment.
</P>
<P>
The war veterans have occupied about 1,500 white farms since
February this year to pressure the government to speed up land
reform. Mugabe had previously supported the war veterans' action.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean government has designated over 3,000 white farms
for seizure to resettle landless war veterans and black peasants.
</P>
</TEXT>
