<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Convicts 151 Falun Gong-related Criminals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 23 (Xinhua) - Chinese courts nationwide, by
August 15, convicted and meted out criminal penalties to 151 hard-
core Falun Gong practitioners who committed crimes, said Ye
Xiaowen, director-general of China's State Administration of
Religious Affairs, at a press conference here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Of the convicted, 22 were given sentences up to five years in
prison, according to Ye, who also serves as an advisor to the
visiting Chinese delegation of religious leaders.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that "the convicted are those who either leaked
state secrets, or making use of Falun Gong to create social chaos,
or committed other crimes."
</P>
<P>
Of the 2.1 million people practicing the Falun Gong cult in
China, those prosecuted are only a tiny fraction, and the majority,
or more than 98 percent, have been converted to normal life after
persuasion and education for over a year, according to the most
senior official in charge of religious affairs in China.
</P>
<P>
In response to local reporters' question on the stance of China
's religious circles on the government crackdown upon the Falun
Gong cult, Buddhist master Sheng Hui said today that the Falun
Gong cult is just as harmful as narcotics, who "has no difference
from drug traffickers."
</P>
<P>
"Due to its strong capability to control the mind of
practitioners, more than 1,600 have committed suicide or been
killed as a result of indulging in practicing the Falun Gong cult,
and 650 people have serious mental problems, of whom 14
perpetrated the felony of homicide," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Buddhist master, who is vice-president of the China
Buddhist Association, said that Buddhists were the first who
identified Falun Gong as an evil cult as early as 1996, three
years ahead of government crackdown, because the cult "stole" many
concepts of Buddhism and distorted them for evil purposes.
</P>
<P>
Both Ye and the Buddhist master warned the public that Falun
Gong is so cunning that it usually takes on different cloaks to
cheat people, which is why it fooled so many people both in China
and the world at large.
</P>
<P>
"When the Chinese Qigong was popular, the master of Falun Gong
Li Hongzhi said he was practicing Qigong for the good of health,
and seeing that religions were respected in China, he said he was
a religious leader," said master Sheng Hui.
</P>
<P>
"He is a wildcatter," he said.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the big advertisements run by the Falun Gong
group in major U.S. newspapers, including the New York Times,
saying that Falun Gong is Qigong again, Ye said that Li Hongzhi is
just playing another trick to fool the public, Ye said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000823.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Policy Is to Move Peace Process Forward: Ben-Ami </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The central task of the Israeli
foreign policy is to move the Middle East peace process forward,
Israeli acting Foreign Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Ever since the Camp David summit in July, the Israeli-
Palestinian negotiators have been meeting with each other and
trying their best to work out the differences on the central issues
in the final-status talks, Ben-Ami told a press conference
organized by the Foreign Press Association.
</P>
<P>
He rejected news reports that the Israeli-Palestinian
negotiators have stoped negotiations since the Camp David, saying
that he himself has been working with Palestinian chief negotiator
Saeb Erekat to try to move the talks ahead.
</P>
<P>
"What we are trying to do is to reach a draft agreement on all
the key issues of the final-status talks by late September, to pave
the way for holding another three-way summit, in which Israeli and
Palestinian leaders can sign it," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Camp David summit in the United States, attended by Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and U.
S. President Bill Clinton, ended on July 25 but failed to reach a
framework agreement on such key issues as the fate of Jerusalem,
borders, Palestinian refugees and Jewish settlements.
</P>
<P>
"The Camp David summit was not a total failure, and progress has
been on the issues of borders, settlements and even the Palestinian
refugees, but not on the Jerusalem issue," he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton had raised three proposals on the Jerusalem issue during
the Camp David summit and one of the them was asking Israelis and
Palestinians to share the sovereignty of the city, but all the
three proposals were rejected by the Palestinian side, he added.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that the Jerusalem issue is too sensitive to settle.
</P>
<P>
Jerusalem has the holy sites for three religions of Jews,
Muslims and Christians. Ben-Ami said Israel will never give up the
Jewish holy site and Jewish quarters in East Jerusalem, but a "
symbolic solution" to the Jerusalem issue must be found.
</P>
<P>
Jerusalem has two parts. The eastern part, or East Jerusalem,
was captured and occupied by Israel during the 1967 Middle East
War. Almost all the holy sites of the three religions are located
in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
As proposed by Clinton, Israel now also prefers to "defer the
settlement" of the Jerusalem issue, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ben-Ami will travel to Egypt on Thursday to hold talks with
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, who has his own proposals for the
settlement of the Jerusalem, and to listen carefully what Mubarak
is going to say.
</P>
<P>
It is urgent for Israel and the Palestinians to reach a peace
agreement, and it's time for the two sides to make final decisions
instead of going to conferences to conferences, he concluded.
</P>
<P>
Ben-Ami met Erekat again Tuesday night to discuss the Jerusalem
and other final-status issues.
</P>
<P>
The renewed talks appeared to be the results of mediation
efforts by U.S. special Middle East peace envoy Dennis Ross, who
has been in the region for a week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000823.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey needs to import 1 million tons of corn to meet
domestic demand for feed grain this year.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Turkish Feed Grain Industrialists Association,
Ulku Karakus, said the country's maize production in the 2000-2001
harvest season is expected to reach around 2 million tons and 1
million tons of imports would be required.
</P>
<P>
The government usually lowers import duty when domestic stocks
run low around the spring, so imports can cover much of the
remaining domestic demand until the next spring.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey would likely have to import 150,000 tons more
of sunflower seed and oil in 2000-2001 than previously expected.
</P>
<P>
Deputy president of the Oilseeds Producers Association, Okyar
Yayarlar, said that this was due to the heat damage to the domestic
crop in July and that the 2000-2001 sunflower crop was of low
quality as well.
</P>
<P>
He said that Turkey normally imports some 600,000 tons of
sunflower seed and oil every year.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The business aviation services company Jet Aviation
plans to enter the United Arab Emirates' Dubai as part of its
expansion in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
"We are monitoring Dubai to see how the business is growing,"
said Norbert Ehrich, vice president and general manager of Jet
Aviation in Saudi Arabia, "Dubai holds the largest potential for
our next operation in the Middle East."
</P>
<P>
Jet Aviation operates more than 140 aircraft with almost 3,500
employees in 30 locations across Europe, East Asia, North and South
America and the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- More residential areas in the UAE's Sharjah emirate
will be connected to the Sharjah natural gas supply network by the
end of this month, according to the Natural Gas Department at
Sharjah Electricity and Water Authority (Sewa).
</P>
<P>
Sewa started the 500-million-dirham (136.6 million U.S. dollars)
piped natural gas supply project in April last year.
</P>
<P>
In the first phase, which was completed earlier this year, 25,
000 consumers in Al Majaz, Bu Shegarah, Al Qassimiyah, Al Manak, Al
Yarmouk and some other areas were covered with direct supply of
natural gas.
</P>
<P>
The second phase started in April this year and is expected to
be completed in mid-2002.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The latest statistics on Egypt's international
cooperation activity during the January-July period this year
disclosed a notable increase in non-refundable grants Egypt
obtained from abroad to 895 million dollars, up 67 percent from the
same period in l999.
</P>
<P>
Total loans during the respective period were 275 million
dollars, down 30 percent from the corresponding period last year.
Combined grants and loans Egypt got during the first seven months
this year hit 1.1 billion dollars, said the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
