<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Promises Major Reform of U.N. Peacekeeping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 23 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan on Wednesday urged world governments to join him in
implementing changes in the structures and management of United
Nations Peace operations recommended by a panel of international
experts.
</P>
<P>
A U.N. panel on peacekeeping operations, which was established
in March at the request of the Secretary-General, launched a
report today in which a clear set of recommendations were made on
how to improve the whole range of U.N. activities in the area of
peace and security.
</P>
<P>
Welcoming the report, Annan said prompt action was "absolutely
essential to make the United Nations truly credible as a force for
peace".
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief asked his deputy, Louise Frechette, to follow up
on implementing the recommendations and to submit an action plan
in time for the General Assembly to consider it during its autumn'
s session.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed the hope that the report would receive
attention from world leaders, who will be in New York next month
for the Millennium Summit.
</P>
<P>
The panel's report recommended extensive restructuring of the
Department of Peacekeeping Operations, a new information and
strategic analysis unit to service all United Nations departments
concerned with peace and security, an integrated task force at the
U.N. Headquarters to plan and support each peacekeeping mission
from its inception, and more systematic use of information
technology.
</P>
<P>
Chaired by Lakhdar Brahimi, a former Algerian Foreign Minister,
the panel included members from all six continents, with wide
experience in humanitarian, development and police work as well as
military peacekeeping.  
</P>
</TEXT>
