<HEADLINE> Defected Libyan Agent to Testify in Lockerbie Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAMP ZEIST, Netherlands, August 23 (Xinhua) -- A former Libyan
secret service agent will testify in the Lockerbie trial next
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The testimony was arranged for next Monday so as to give the
defense team time to study crucial documents to be released by the
United States secret service CIA.
</P>
<P>
Abdul Majid Giaka, the former Libyan agent who became U.S.
double agent shortly before the Lockerbie bombing, was originally
due to appear in court on Wednesday but the defense team objected,
persuading judges that the CIA documents could contain information
that turn out critical to the case of its client.
</P>
<P>
The prosecution said that Abdel Basset al-Megrahi and Al-Amin
Khalifa Fahima while posing as Libyan Arab Airlines employees in
Malta put stolen luggage transfer tags to an unaccompanied
suitcase that contained the bomb.
</P>
<P>
The suitcase passed through an X-ray scanner at Frankfurt
before being loaded onto the New York-bound Pan Am Flight 103 that
blew up over Lockerbie on December 21, 1988, killing 270 people
altogether.
</P>
<P>
The prosecution had planned to introduce a batch of cable
communications from CIA agents in Malta to Washington containing
details of interviews with the defected Libyan agent.
</P>
<P>
The cable communications, combined with the testimony by Giaka
in court, are expected to serve as the key evidence to the
accusation against the two Libyans.
</P>
<P>
The defense team argued that the copies of the cable
communications should not be allowed as evidence in that the
prosecution had seen largely unedited copies in early June whereas
the defense had only seen copies with sections and words blanked
out on grounds that they are either sensitive or irrelevant
information.
</P>
<P>
The prosecution told the court that Chief Prosecutor Colin Boyd
had met with CIA officials overnight and progress was being made
in the declassification of the cable communications that would be
given to the defense team.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutor Alastair Campbell said on Wednesday that the defense
team would be given the copies of the cable communications by
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The prosecution also said that Giaka was assistant manager of
the Libyan Arab Airlines in Malta before defecting to the United
States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
