<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania to Open Fresh Talks with IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The Romanian government will
open fresh talks on Thursday with a delegation of the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) for the release of the second
installment of a standby loan agreement.
</P>
<P>
The standby agreement, approved in August 1999 by the IMF board,
includes a credit of 547 million U.S. dollars, of which Romania
received only the first tranche of 73 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
IMF representative in Bucharest, Stephane Cosse, said that if
talks end successfully, Romania will be disbursed the second
tranche of the standby agreement worth 110 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
"The IMF mission that will come to Bucharest has two goals: the
first refers to a second revision of the standby agreement and the
second to an analysis of the evolution of the whole economy over
the past year," Cosse was cited on Wednesday as saying by the
official Rompres news agency.
</P>
<P>
Such analysis is not conducted for Romania alone, Cosse said,
adding that the IMF regulation calls for such annual assessment
for the economy of all member-states.
</P>
<P>
IMF's technical mission will make a complete assessment of all
economic indicators, in a more complex manner, which does not
refer only to the way that the Fund's resources are used, Cosse
said.
</P>
<P>
The IMF official said that there are a number of good signals
in the Romanian economy, such as economic growth, beneficial
developments of the trade balance and boosted exports. "Inflation
is the most unsettling aspect. The inflation target should be
revised," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Romanian Government set an inflation rate target of 27
percent for this year, a goal it will not be able to meet.
</P>
<P>
In reference to this situation, Finance Ministry's secretary of
state Valentin Lazea, who will participate in the talks with the
IMF, evoked a range of "reasons for which the Government cannot be
held responsible".
</P>
<P>
He cited the floods and drought that hit Romania this year, a
lower exchange rate for the euro and the dramatic oil price rises.
Finance from the international bodies, moreover, was disbursed as
late as this June, four months later than promised.
</P>
</TEXT>
