<HEADLINE> Thai Government to Share Diesel Price Hikes Cost With Truckers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government has agreed
with a group of protesting truckers to share the cost of diesel
price hikes, according to a government report late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
After a meeting between Thai transportation minister Suthep
Thueksuban and representatives of the truckers Wednesday, both
sides agreed that the current diesel price of 14.90 baht (37 U.S.
cents per liter is "unfair," and the normal price should be 10.82
baht (26 U.S. cents) and the government will share the cost of
extra, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, about 1,000 trucks from four neighboring
provinces formed a protest convoy in the highways outside Bangkok,
demanding that the government should help to ease the impact of
fuel price hikes.
</P>
<P>
The government's move was welcomed by Thai Transportation
Association chairman Chatchawal Pojananuphab, who said that the
government has shown it was sincerely concerned with the truckers.
</P>
<P>
As the world oil price soaring to a ten-year's high, Thailand's
petrol and diesel prices have increased three times in two weeks.
The government is facing criticisms for being slow to take
measures to moderate the price hikes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
