<HEADLINE> Government to Focus on Economic Development: Iranian President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad Khatami
said here Wednesday that his government will do more in future to
promote the country's economic development.
</P>
<P>
Khatami said at the inauguration ceremony of a big housing
project in the south of Tehran that future policies of the
government will be based on encouraging production, absorbing
domestic and foreign investments and efficiently utilizing the rich
national resources.
</P>
<P>
"We have no option but to encourage production and investments
in the country and raise national income," he was quoted by the
official Islamic Republic News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that his government will show more care for the low
and fixed income group so that they will not be harmed by the
process of development.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the housing requirements of the people should be
met. If the needy are provided with housing, a major part of the
society's problems will be solved, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the 10,000 rental units of the newly inaugurated project
will be completed by September and qualified applicants will be
allocated the houses at mere 30 percent of the total cost price.
</P>
<P>
Khatami's government, formed in 1997, has been focusing on
political and social reforms in the past three years, which invited
severe criticism and resistance from the powerful conservatives.
</P>
<P>
The country's longtime economic problems, notably high inflation
and unemployment, have not been eased in the past three years.
</P>
<P>
Khatami has announced that he will seek reelection in the next
presidential election, possibly to be held in May 2001. 
</P>
