<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Indonesia's New Cabinet to Face Tough Tasks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 23 -- Indonesian President Abdurrahman Wahid
here Wednesday announced his new cabinet lineup, with significant
changes. It is believed that the move is aimed at boosting his
administration performance for the next four years.
</P>
<P>
Some prominent figures from political parties as well as
professionals were recruited into what Wahid said as a "
collaboration cabinet team."
</P>
<P>
To boost the efficiency of the new cabinet, Wahid has expressed
his willingness to authorize Vice President Megawati Soekarno
Puteri to carry out the government's technical daily work. But,
the vice president should be responsible for the president.
</P>
<P>
It also could be categorized as a brave decision, as Wahid has
liquidated at least ten ministries and retained only 25 ministries/
departments.
</P>
<P>
The new cabinet is simpler and slimmer, and will enable the
executives to be able to make a "fast decision" as there is no
longer a long bureaucratic procedures that used to be passed
through.
</P>
<P>
As the country is facing with many complicated problems in an
unusual political transition period, all the ministers should be
prepared themselves to work harder.
</P>
<P>
The first priority for the new cabinet is recovering the crisis-
hit economy which will provide job opportunities, boost the
currency of rupiah, and help the development of small and medium
industries.
</P>
<P>
Other crucial tasks are finalizing banking restructuring
programs and continuing the privatization of state-owned companies.
</P>
<P>
The new cabinet should also be able to improve the current
political and security condition to bring back foreign investors
as well as re-running economic activities without fear of possible
disturbances and riots.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government should put an end to the rising
separatist activities in some areas, such as Aceh, Irian Jaya.
</P>
<P>
Another knotty problem must be solved is eliminating corruption,
especially the trial of former president Soeharto who was accused
of embezzling state funds during his 32 years in power.
</P>
<P>
Observers held that the government must seriously pay its
attention to its job. If all the problems could be resolved step
by step, the ongoing political and economic reforms in the country
will make progress and the government's prestige will also be
raised.
</P>
<P>
A conducive climate following the success of the People's
Consultative Assembly (MPR) annual session should be maintained.
Horizontal conflicts, which have been taking place in several
areas in the country, should be completely overcome and the
upholding of the supremacy of law has to be enhanced, political
analysts noted.
</P>
<P>
The formation of the new cabinet seems to be one of Wahid's
efforts to stay in power until 2004.
</P>
<P>
However, Speaker of the parliament Akbar Tandjung has said that
if Wahid fails to improve the current situation, he is likely to
lose people's confidence and it means he will face big trouble in
the following years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000823.0056 </DOCNO>
