<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Impose Price Ceiling on Medicines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Senate President
Franklin Drilon said Wednesday he is open to impose price ceiling
on medicines citing that prices of drugs have reached alarming
proportions compared with those in other Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
But Drilon said this move will only be undertaken as a last
resort to arrest the spiraling prices of medicines in the
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
"The survey data on the comparative prices of medicines are
very alarming. We do not need to wonder why the poor and the
deprived die faster than the ones who can afford," Drilon said
here in speech during the oath-taking ceremonies of new
pharmacists.
</P>
<P>
Drilon said he is against any government subsidy for medicines
or price control because these measures ignore the basic problem
of high medicine prices and do not offer a lasting solution to the
problem.
</P>
<P>
However, if the government can not come up with effective
measures to bring down drug prices, he said, he would support some
form of price control if this would be the only way to solve the
problem.
</P>
<P>
The Senate chief also supports government plans to bypass local
and foreign pharmaceutical companies and instead import directly
the drug requirements of government hospitals.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Drilon filed a resolution asking the Senate committees
on health and trade to conduct a joint probe into the excessive
pricing of medicines and introduce legislative measures to make
medicines more affordable to the people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
