<HEADLINE> Singapore's MICE Industry Expands in First Half Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's meetings,
incentives, conventions and exhibitions (MICE) industry expanded
significantly in the first half of this year compared to the
corresponding period last year, Singapore Tourism Board (STB)
announced this in a statement Wednesday while announcing that
Singapore ranked among the top five convention city in the world.
</P>
<P>
STB said that the Belgium-based Union des Association
Internatinales (UAI) conducted annual statistical survey and
ranked Singapore world's fifth convention city -- the highest
ranking the island country ever achieved.
</P>
<P>
The total number of events staged in Singapore increased by 7.8
percent to 3,245 in 1999 and the number of conventions rose by 23.
8 percent to 880, STB added.
</P>
<P>
Referring to major exhibitions and conventions held in
Singapore from January to June this year, the STB cited the Asian
Aerospace, Food &AMP; Hotel Asia, CommunicAsia and Tax Free Asia
Pacific and the inaugural International Dental Exhibition and
Meeting (IDEM)
</P>
<P>
"CommunicAsia, Asia Pacific's largest communications and IT
event which took place in June, brought in 16,000 overseas
visitors. Food&AMP;Hotel Asia generated 22,000 foreign participants,"
STB elaborated.
</P>
<P>
The IDEM brought in 4,000 overseas delegates in April and has
also confirmed Singapore as the venue for its conventions in 2002,
2004 and 2006, STB added.
</P>
<P>
Six large meetings by IT companies have since been confirmed
and will bring in close to 3,500 overseas delegates between
September this year and July 2001 with four of them to be staged
in Asia for the first time, STB said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
