<HEADLINE> Four-Team Trade Failure Irks Knicks Fans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The proposed four-team 13-
player blockbuster trade, which would have been the biggest in NBA
history, is dead for now, and legendary New York Knicks center
Patrick Ewing remains struck in a city that doesn't seem to want
him.
</P>
<P>
New York fans and media hailed the trade, which also would have
involved the Los Angeles Lakers, Detroit Pistons and Seattle
SuperSonics and sent Ewing to Seattle, as a brilliant move when it
appeared to be a done deal.
</P>
<P>
The trade unraveled as the Pistons developed cold feet late
Monday after agreeing to it Sunday. The teams still were trying
to salvage the deal Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Fans have blamed Ewing for the Knicks' failure to win an NBA
title in his 15-year career with the team, even though he was
voted one of the 50 greatest players in league history. The deal
was considered a step in the right direction to move the Knicks
past the injury-plagued disappointment of the Ewing years.
</P>
<P>
"His ego was too big, David Robinson stepped aside for Tim
Duncan, and the Spurs won a championship. If Ewing had done that,
the Knicks probably would have done the same thing," the New York
Post said.
</P>
<P>
In the proposed four-team trade, Pistons would have gotten
seven marginal players, cash from New York and a first-round draft
pick each from the Knicks and Lakers.
</P>
<P>
Apparently Detroit and many of its fans felt that they were
getting the short end of the stick. Meanwhile, the Pistons turned
their attention elsewhere and Tuesday traded point guard Lindsey
Hunter to the Milwaukee Bucks for forward Billy Owens. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
