<DOCNO> XIE20000823.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Supreme Court Rejects Former Shas Leader's Appeal Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Supreme Court President
Justice Aharon Barak Wednesday rejected an appeal by the former
leader of the ultra-Orthodox Shas party Aryeh Deri for a new
hearing of his case.
</P>
<P>
Deri, the first former cabinet minister ever sentenced to prison
terms in the country, will begin serving a three-year sentence on
September 3.
</P>
<P>
Last month, a three-judge panel upheld the lower court verdict,
but reduced Deri's prison term from four to three years. The fine
on Deri was also reduced. Deri, 41, was ordered to begin serving
the prison term on August 13.
</P>
<P>
Deri's lawyer has requested a new hearing before a full panel of
justices. The move had delayed Deri's sentence serving.
</P>
<P>
Shas party leader Eli Yishai said on Wednesday that it is a sad
day and a pity that the president of the Supreme Court has denied
Deri the chance of a second hearing.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on Israel Radio, Yishai said despite their
disappointment, Shas supporters are moderate and will not resort to
violence and criticism of the court.
</P>
<P>
Yishai said Deri will be escorted to prison when he begins
serving his term and the Shas leadership will continue consulting
with him while he is in prison.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem District Court convicted Deri, the country's
former youngest interior minister in history, of taking bribes
totalling 155,000 U.S. dollars from three friends and co-defendants
- Moshe and Aryeh Weinberg and Yom Tov Rubin, as well as fraud and
breach of trust.
</P>
<P>
The conviction was delivered on March 17, 1999, following a
trial that lasted five years. A three-judge panel ruled unanimously
that Deri pocketed the money over a period of five years from 1985
to 1989 in return for channelling state funds to the Weinberg-Rubin
yeshiva.
</P>
<P>
On April 14, 1999, Deri was sentenced to four years in prison
and fined 250,000 shekels (about 62,500 dollars) or another 10
months in prison in lieu of the fine.
</P>
<P>
The court also ruled that the count of bribery constituted moral
turpitude, meaning that if Deri's appeal is rejected, he will not
be able to run for public office for 10 years after completing his
prison term.
</P>
<P>
The sentence caused a furor in Shas's constituency, which
revered the charismatic young politician and one of the country's
most powerful people. Six weeks later, Shas won 17 seats in the
Knesset (Parliament) elections, up from 10 three years earlier. The
party thus rose to the status of the third largest party after
Labor and the Likud.
</P>
<P>
In another reaction to the Supreme Court ruling on Wednesday,
Shas Knesset Member Eli Suissa said the refusal to Deri's second
appeal is "another stab of knife into the body of the Sephardic
Jewish community." He said the day will mark the beginning of
violence of the Sephardic Jewish revolution in Israel and
throughout the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000823.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
