<DOCNO> XIE20000823.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Records 8.8 Percent GDP Growth in 2nd Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's real gross
domestic product (GDP) expanded by 8.8 percent in the second
quarter of this year against 11.9 percent growth in the first
quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
GDP growth for the first half of this year is now estimated at
10.3 percent against 1.8 percent in the first half of 1999 and
this exceeds the levels attained in the second half of 1999 by 2.4
percent, Bank Negara (State Bank) Governor Zeti Akhtar Aziz said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The second quarter this year was the fifth consecutive quarter
of positive growth for Malaysia's economy which contracted
following the regional financial crisis in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The governor said output expansion had raised the level of the
GDP to 52.4 billion ringgit (13.78 billion U.S. dollars),
surpassing the highest quarterly GDP of 51.2 billion ringgit (13.
47 billion U.S.dollars) recorded in the fourth quarter of 1997.
</P>
<P>
She said "8.8 percent was considered a very strong growth for
Malaysia. What is important here is that there is sustainable
growth. We want this (growth) to be sustained over the medium to
long term and the growth momentum is continuing."
</P>
<P>
The manufacturing sector recorded a growth of 22 percent in the
second quarter against 10.7 percent in the previous corresponding
period.
</P>
<P>
The construction sector grew by 2.1 percent against a
contraction of 7.9 percent, mining grew by 2.5 percent against a
contraction of 4.6 percent, services rose by 5.0 percent against 1.
4 percent but agriculture, forestry and fishing declined by 4.8
percent against a growth of 9.9 percent previously.
</P>
<P>
Real gross fixed capital formation increased by 25.8 percent in
the second quarter reflecting investment in new growth areas such
as information technology and higher investment for expansion of
production capacity.
</P>
<P>
The inflation rate in the second quarter was at 1.4 percent due
to lower prices and lower price increases for food. Inflation is
expected to be lower than the earlier forecast of 3.0 percent for
the whole year.
</P>
<P>
The trade surplus of 12.5 billion ringgit (3.28 billion U.S.
dollars) contributed to the increase in international reserves of
Bank Negara Malaysia to 129.2 billion ringgit (34 billion U.S.
dollars) at the of June this year.
</P>
<P>
In the second quarter, exports continued to increase strongly
by 16.9 percent while imports grew by 31.5 percent mainly due to
the strong external demand for exports and increased investment
activities.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's external debt position continued to remain at a
manageable level, with total external debts recording a modest
increase of 0.5 percent to 155.8 billion ringgit (41 billion U.S.
dollars) at the end of June 2000, she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
