<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Ruling Coalition Troubled by Infighting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's ruling People's
Alliance (PA) was troubled by a political infighting between two
Muslim ministers in the run-up to the general elections due in
October, government officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Shipping Minister Mohammed Ashraff, leader of the Sri Lanka
Moslem Congress (SLMC), resigned from the cabinet on Tuesday in
protest over criticism from his colleague, Transport Minister A.H.
M. Fowzie.
</P>
<P>
Fowzie on Tuesday issued a statement slamming the SLMC over the
party's demand for a higher quota of seats at the October 10
parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
He said the party was a spent force which cannot get more than
five seats in the forthcoming general elections unless they
contest with the PA.
</P>
<P>
The SLMC said Wednesday it had decided that any future support
for the PA would depend on the action President Chandrika
Kumaratunga takes against Fowzie. Kumaratunga's PA was able to
form a government after the 1994 elections with a slender one-seat
majority mainly due to support from the SLMC, which had seven
lawmakers in the 225-member parliament.
</P>
<P>
President Kumaratunga, unwilling to lose SLMC's crucial support,
has refused to accept Ashraff's resignation.
</P>
<P>
However, crucial talks between the SLMC and Kumaratunga for the
party to contest with the PA were reported to be deadlocked on
Wednesday with the party insisting on demanding three seats and
two ministries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
