<HEADLINE> Myanmar Govt Calls for NLD's Contribution to Education Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The Myanmar government Wednesday
called on the National League for Democracy (NLD), an opposition
political party in the country, to contribute meaningfully and
positively to the education sector.
</P>
<P>
The call came one month after all universities in Myanmar were
reopened in late July without official announcement following a
long closure since December 1996 for students' involvement in
street demonstrations then against the government.
</P>
<P>
"The government together with the people of Myanmar welcomes
any meaningful contribution and cooperation from political parties
within the country to help overcome challenges and create a better
educational standard for its youths and a better life for its
people," the government said in an Information Sheet released here
Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
However, the information sheet expressed regret that the NLD,
which it said, has taken the stance of condemning and criticizing
the government's endeavors in encouraging the students to
peacefully pursue their education without being side-tracked and
exploited by certain quarters with vested interest.
</P>
<P>
The information sheet pointed out that the government has been
working hard to assure the children better education, which is a
national priority, by investing more and more in schools not only
to open the doors of learning to all but also to obtain higher
standards and quality of learning.
</P>
<P>
The information sheet added that the government appreciates
constructive advice and criticism from the local and international
community, while rejecting criticizing and condemning others
merely for the sake of engaging in the act of confrontation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the NLD charged in a recent statement that
educational crisis is among crisis that the government faces in
the fields of politics, economy, social and international affairs,
urging the government to tackle the country's present overall
crisis by implementing the result of the 1990 multi-party general
election, in which the NLD won a vast majority of parliamentary
seats with 396 out of 485. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
