<HEADLINE> Manila Vows to Handle Abu Sayyaf Problem by Itself </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada said Wednesday that the Philippine government is capable
of resolving the problem with the Abu Sayyaf without the help of
foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
Estrada made this statement in response to the reported offer
by the United States and Malaysia to help in the fight against the
terrorist group.
</P>
<P>
"We don't need it. We can handle this on our own," said the
president before flying to Mindanao for the third phase of his
series of visits to the South aimed at monitoring development
projects there.
</P>
<P>
Press Undersecretary Mike Toledo said although the government
welcomes the offer of Malaysia and the United States to help in
the fight against global terrorism, it maintains that the hostage
crisis involving the Abu Sayyaf group is an internal matter.
</P>
<P>
Toledo also stressed that suggestions to create a multinational
armed forces to combat the Abu Sayyaf is not necessary.
</P>
<P>
"The military option in neutralizing the Abu Sayyaf is not
being discussed because right now, what is important is the safe
release of all the hostages," Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohammad and U.S. Embassy
spokesman Thomas Skipper were earlier reported as saying that
their governments are prepared to help the Philippines combat the
Abu Sayyaf, since they consider the group a terrorist organization.
</P>
<P>
The foreign hostages, now being held by the Abu Sayyaf, were
originally abducted from a diving resort in Sipadan, Malaysia in
April and were later brought to Sulu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
