<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Opposition Stands for Self-defense Strategy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The Australian defense strategy
must be based on the defense of Australia, Kim Beasley stressed.
</P>
<P>
The Opposition leader was addressing to the Sydney Security
Forum last Friday and it was published by The Australian daily
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He said it must be the discipline to determine priorities for
Australian Defense Force capability development.
</P>
<P>
Australia cannot and should not structure its defense force
directly in relation to our alliances or potential diplomatic
needs, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
"We certainly should not structure the Australian Defense Force
on the basis of forward defense contingencies, such as conflict on
the Korean peninsula, across the Taiwan Strait and in the South
China Sea," Beazley said and added that "we need to contribute to
diplomatic strategies aimed at preventing such tensions becoming
shooting wars."
</P>
<P>
He accused the Howard Government of ignoring "any real
consideration of the defense benefits of enhancing Australia's
engagement with the region".
</P>
<P>
"No more important foreign policy issue faces us than advancing
our engagement with Asia," he said.
</P>
<P>
In Australia, a debate on the defense strategy is undergoing.
The focus is whether and how much the defense spending should be
increased and the Defense Forces' mission should be to defend
Australia itself or as the United States' strategic prop to guard
the whole interest and value of the West in the region.
</P>
<P>
There is a strong cry that Australia must increase sharply its
defense spending and raise the armed forces' overseas battle
capability, and in case the United States involves in any military
clashes in the region, Australia should be able to take concert
operations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
