<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Stocks End Fall 1.36 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong stocks ended lower
Wednesday, pulled down by the weak telecom stocks and selling
pressure of blue chips.
</P>
<P>
The Hang Seng Index plunged 240.88 points, or 1.36 percent, to
finish Wednesday's session at 17,427.40.
</P>
<P>
The turnover was 12.034 billion HK dollars (1.542 billion U.S.
dollars), up 1.197 billion HK dollars (153 million U.S. dollars)
over the 10.837 billion HK dollars (1.389 billion U.S. dollars) of
the previous trading session.
</P>
<P>
Dealers attributed the Index sharp fall to the weak telecom
stocks, with China Mobile leading the downward by losing 3.19
percent. Profit-taking on banking and other blue chips also
dragged down the Hang Seng Index.
</P>
<P>
Of the four sub-indices, only Properties registered gains of 0.
20 percent, while Finance, Utilities and Commerce &AMP; Industry lost
0.41 percent, 0.64 percent and 2.41 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
China-related shares ended lower with the Hang Seng China
Enterprises Index down 3.66 percent and the Hang Seng China-
Affiliated Corp Index down 3.55 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Hang Seng IT Index and Hang Seng IT Portfolio Index fell 3.
10 percent and 2.74 percent.
</P>
<P>
The blue chips went up 40.80 points, or 0.23 percent, to open
at 17,709.08 Wednesday. But selling pressure soon offset the
previous gains with the morning session closed down 82.26 points,
or 0.47 percent, at 17,568.02. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
