<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing to Hold Sixth Major Cities' Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The Sixth Major Cities' Summit
is scheduled for September 27-30 in Beijing, said a spokesman at
today's press conference organized by the Beijing municipal
government.
</P>
<P>
The Sixth Major Cities' Summit, whose theme is "City
Development and Cooperation in the 21st Century," will focus on
such issues of common concern as development strategies,
construction and administration of cities as well as cooperation
and exchanges between them, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Mao, vice-mayor of Beijing and vice-chairman and
secretary-general of the summit's organizing committee, said at
the press conference that the event will mark another important
step in the development of Beijing as an international metropolis.
</P>
<P>
The summit will also help promote friendly relations between
the countries participating in the meeting, said Zhang.
</P>
<P>
The Major Cities' Summit started in 1985, and is held every
three years. Until now, Tokyo, Istanbul, Montreal, Berlin and
Moscow had held the past five sessions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
