<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Cypriot Leader Calls for State of Emergency in Northern Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash has said that a state of emergency might be the best way
to deal with a worsening economic crisis and social tension in his
breakaway republic, the Cyprus Mail newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Street protesters earlier this month called for Denktash and
his "government" to resign over their handling of a series of bank
failures in northern Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
"Our people are experiencing difficult times, and everyone is
looking for a way out," the paper quoted Denktash as saying.
</P>
<P>
"I am suggesting declaring a state of emergency may be a way
out," he said, adding that some "coercive measures" were necessary
to right the economy.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has criticised the way the Turkish Cypriot "government"
has managed its heavily subsidized economy, and Denktash is also
under fire for his perceived role in Ankara's dominance of the
Turkish Cypriot economy and state.
</P>
<P>
Denktash earlier this month attended the U.N.-sponsored
proximity talks on Cyprus issue with Greek Cypriot leader, the
Cyprus president Glafcos Clerides, in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
Crowds called for his resignation when a Turkish Cypriot court
last month released a newspaper editor accused of espionage after
questioning the Turkish military's control over the police and fire
brigade in northern Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Denktash denied that a state of emergency would create an
autocracy.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of an abortive coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots unilaterally declared in 1983 a breakaway
state which is only recognized by Ankara. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
