<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks End High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 23 (Xinhua) - The Australian sharemarket ended
high Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
For the second day running the all ordinaries index closed at a
record high, adding 9.8 points to 3,322.7. The S&AMP;P/ASX 200 gained
11 points to 3,364.4.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 550.5 million shares worth $1.49 billion.
Falls beat rises by 897 to 725, with 598 stocks steady.
</P>
<P>
Reynolds and Co director Peter Struk said the fall in the
Australian dollar, which was boosting resource stocks, was a key
factor in the market's fortunes today.
</P>
<P>
The weak Australian dollar helps the resource export.
</P>
<P>
Rio Tinto was the strongest of the miners, surging 1.028
Australian dollar to 27.688 Australian dollars, BHP rose 17.1
cents to 19.521 Australian dollars and WMC added 21.8 cents to 8.
28 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the media sector, News Corp put on 64.5 cents to 22.795
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The telco sector was gloom, Telstra easing five cents to 7.15
Australian dollars. Cable &AMP; Wireless Optus shed 16.1 cents to 4.
309 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the finance sector, the big four banks were higher with the
exception of NAB, which dropped 6.5 cents to 25.685 Australian
dollars. Commonwealth added 18.2 cents to 28.912 Australian
dollars, ANZ rose 27 cents to 13.21 Australian dollars and Westpac
rallied 38 cents to 12.85 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
AMP lifted 12.4 cents to 17.88 Australian dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
