<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Dives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar ended two
U.S. cents lower Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar dipped as low as 56.90 U.S. cents on the
day and closed at 57.15 U.S. cents from 59.03 on the previous day.
</P>
<P>
Richard Yetsenga, currency strategist at Deutsche Bank, said
the offshore traders had bailed out of the Australian dollar
because it had failed to make progress.
</P>
<P>
Faced with a sharply weaker currency this morning the local
market had tried to buy it back but the selling barrage was too
strong.
</P>
<P>
The selling barrage was exacerbated by a fall to three-month
lows in euro/U.S. dollar rates while the euro dive was triggered
by poor sentiment implied in a German business survey which gave
the market cause to believe the European Central Bank will be in
no hurry to lift rates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
