<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Earthquakes Cause Damages in Northeastern Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 23 (Xinhua) -- A series of earthquakes occurred
late Tuesday and early Wednesday in Iran's northeastern province of
Khorasan, causing damages, but no report of casualties is
available, the Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
A quake measuring 5.4 degrees on the Richter scale rocked the
city of Bojnourd at about 21:25 local time (1655 GMT) Tuesday
night. The Geophysics Institute of Tehran University
registered the
epicenter of the quake at 100 kilometers northwest of the city, on
Iran's border with Turkmenistan.
</P>
<P>
The 5.4-degree quake was followed by two tremors, which measured
4.9 and 3.8 degrees respectively. And early Wednesday, some 45
aftershocks, all measuring over 2.5 degrees, jarred the city and
nearby areas again.
</P>
<P>
The IRNA report said the earthquakes caused damages in some
villages, without elaborating. But there are no reports of
casualties.
</P>
<P>
Reminiscent of a destructive earthquake that took place in the
province in February 1997, inhabitants spent the entire night
outdoors fearing aftershocks, the report said. A Red Cross team has
been reportedly dispatched to the area.
</P>
<P>
Earthquakes are not unusual in Iran, as the country is located
on an earthquake belt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000823.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE Editorial Urges Arab Summit, Defiance of Foreign Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, August 23 (Xinhua) -- A major Arabic daily of the
United Arab Emirates has urged Arab nations to defy foreign force
and hold an Arab summit in their own interests.
</P>
<P>
The Abu Dhabi-based Al Ittihad published Wednesday pointed out
in its editorial that "a foreign hand, which never wish something
good for the Arab nation" was pulling the string behind the screen
and was holding the "magic wand" that can cause the summit to be or
not to be. wondered the paper.
</P>
<P>
"This foreign hand continues to pull every sort of tricks to
ensure that the Arab front is always divided and that no summit is
held to patch up Arab differences," the editorial said.
</P>
<P>
It also said the hand is busy "ensuring the safety of Israel and
strengthening the Jewish state's position in the Middle East peace
process."
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the paper expressed disappointment at the
Arab leaders' inability to convene a summit to solve many critical
issues threatening the Arab nation's entity.
</P>
<P>
The paper wondered why some quarters shy away from convening an
Arab summit with intangible excuses, including their claim that
such a summit needs adequate preparation.
</P>
<P>
The Arab situation is not that bad to warrant a failure in
holding such a meeting, which would surely lead to making some
critical decisions, it called.
</P>
<P>
It noted that the problem of Arabs lies not in the call for
holding a summit but in the Arab leaders' inability to understand
such a call and to critically study it from all perspectives before
making a final decision.
</P>
<P>
"It is high time for Arabs to live abreast with their current
situation. It is only by so doing that they will realize how
important it is to hold an Arab summit now," the paper stressed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000823.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The United Arab Emirates (UAE) is set to build 25
new dams to combat drought as one of the priorities in the budget
proposal to be submitted for cabinet approval, the Dubai-based Gulf
News daily reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Agriculture and Fisheries Saeed Mohammad Al-
Ragabani said that the new budget proposal for 2000-2002 will be
ready within a week. The proposal covers projects that will be
undertaken in the next five years, such as the construction of 25
new dams in different parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan has received a grant of 40 million euro (36.4
million U.S. dollars) from the European Union (EU), the first batch
of an EU grant of 80 million euro (72.8 million dollars) scheduled
for the year 2000, Jordanian officials said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Another 40 million euro (36.4 million dollars) will be dispensed
by the end of the year to help the economic reforms, privatization
drive and budgetary deficit management of the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
The 80-million-euro grant was part of a aid package signed
between Jordan and the EU in April, which totalled 129 million euro
(117.4 million dollars) if soft loans and investments are included.
</P>
<P>
The EU is one of the biggest donors and aid providers to the
kingdom after the United States and Japan.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Oman has signed contracts with an Indian company
and an European-Japanese consortium to build two gas pipelines by
the second half of 2002 at a total cost of 304 million U.S.
dollars, the
Dubai-based Gulf News daily reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The two pipelines, one running from central Oman to Sohar on the
coast north of capital Muscat, and the other from the northwest to
the southern port city of Salalah, will be completed within two
years, the Oman Gas Company was quoted by the paper as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Indian company Dodsal signed a contract for the construction
of the 700-kilometer Salalah line at a cost of 180 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Saipem and Snamprogetti of Italy with the Athens-based
Consolidated Contractors International Co. and Mitsubishi signed a
contract for the 305-kilometer Sohar line worth 124 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Work on both pipelines is expected to start in late 2000.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- SATYAM Infoway Limited, India's largest private
Internet service provider (ISP), will send a technical team to
Dubai shortly to look for business opportunities in the United Arab
Emirates and the Gulf region, reported the official WAM news agency
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
R.Ramaraj, managing director and chief executive officer of
SATYAM Infoway said in Dubai that there are various net-related
activities where his company could find a suitable market in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Among others, businesses in the region would need end-to-end
solution for transforming into the new economy, while SATYAM would
also offer web-related services, like designing and hosting
services
apart from providing e-commerce solutions.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The Sheikh Mohammed IT Project for Schools launched
in the United Arab Emirates (UAE) will extend its expertise to
private schools throughout the country in its third phase, the
official WAM news agency reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Jamal Khalfan Al Huwairb, director of www.sheikhmohammed.co.ae,
said that the second phase of the project to equip all public
schools in Dubai with IT labs was completed last month.
</P>
<P>
It was exclusively formatted and designed by pioneering IT
companies - IBM with its equipment, Lotus with its solutions and
Cisco Systems with its IT academies and education programs.
</P>
</TEXT>
