<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Investments in Philippine Economic Zones Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Investments in the Philippines'
major economic and industrial zones zoomed up by 10 billion pesos
(250 million U.S. dollars) for the first seven months of this year,
or an 8.85 percent increase compared with the same period in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Trade and Industry (DTI) said Wednesday in a
report that investments at the Philippine Economic Zones Authority
(PEZA), Subic Bay Metropolitan Authority (SBMA) and the Clark
Development Coporation (CDC) amounted to 130.8 billion pesos (3.27
billion dollars), compared to 120.161 billion pesos (3 billion
dollars) for the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Although there was a slump in investments registered in the
Board of Investment (BOI) for the seven-month period, this was
offset by the surge in investments in PEZA, SBMA and CDC, the
report said. The BOI is one of the major investment management
institutes of the DTI.
</P>
<P>
Data from the DTI showed that foreign investments registered in
the BOI for the first seven months of 2000 dropped 63 percent from
a year earlier to 17.46 billion pesos (436.5 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The report noted that because of the limited incentive package
offered by BOI, investors now opt to take advantage of the more
generous incentive package of PEZA, SBMA and CDC.
</P>
<P>
Since 1997, according to the report, BOI-registered firms have
been no longer entitled to tax and duty-free importation of
capital equipment incentives, the main reason for the decline in
BOI investment registrations.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the PEZA, CDC and SBMA aside from offering
income tax holidays, also allow importation of capital equipment
and the choice of paying 5 percent on gross income in lieu of
paying all the national and local taxes, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
