<HEADLINE> China Asked to Share Paddy Cultivation Expertise with Sabah </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's state of Sabah,
which plans to venture into large scale paddy cultivation, has
requested China to lend its expertise in the field.
</P>
<P>
China, as a major exporter of rice, could share its expertise
in the state's plan to be self-sufficient in rice production, the
state Chief Minister, Osu Sukam said in a statement Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Sabah wishes to see its good trade relations with China expand
into other areas as well, particularly fisheries, tourism and the
herbal industry, the chief minister said in the statement issued
after meeting China's Deputy Agriculture Minister Liu Jian who is
on five-day visit to the state in East Malaysia to enhance and
explore areas of bilateral cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Sabah currently produces 30 percent of its rice consumption and
imports the rest, mainly from Thailand and China.
</P>
<P>
Sabah's major exports to China are palm oil and rubberwood and
it also exports substantial volume of fish, prawns and fresh
flowers to China with Hong Kong as the gateway. 
</P>
</TEXT>
