<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Palestinian and Israeli negotiators met Tuesday night in a
session characterized by Palestinian officials as a resumption of
intensive negotiations aimed at resolving the question of Jerusalem
and other final-status issues.
</P>
<P>
The renewed talks appeared to be the result of mediation efforts
by U.S special envoy Dennis Ross, who has been in the region for
nearly a week to prod the sides to bridge the differences.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- King Abdullah II of Jordan came to Israel on Tuesday on his
second visit to the country since ascending throne in February
1999. During his meeting with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak,
Abdullah said Syrian President Bashar al-Assad is interested in
renewing negotiations with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Barak told the king that he is ready to make progress on the
stalled Syrian track, but warned of the need to be careful because
of the sensitive state of negotiations with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
According to a senior diplomatic source in Jerusalem, "Israel
does not want to appear as if it is trying to bypass the
Palestinians on its way to the Syrians."
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- The dollar continued to weaken against the Israeli currency,
the shekel, on Tuesday. At the outset, the greenback was trading at
4.028 shekels and continued to slide down until the representative
rate was set at 4.024 shekels, a 0.17 percent drop on the previous
rate.
</P>
<P>
The flow of foreign capital into Israel continues unabated and
is expected to add more downward pressure on the dollar.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Abdullah reaffirmed his support for Palestinian sovereignty
over east Jerusalem at a meeting Tuesday with Palestinian National
Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat in the West Bank city of Ramallah.
</P>
<P>
The king also urged the Israel and the Palestinians to continue
working toward a peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
The king suggested recognizing Israeli sovereignty over the
Western Wall, Judaism's holiest site, and Palestinian sovereignty
over the Al-Aqsa mosque in the Old City of Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
