<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Stocks Down Despite Steady U.S. Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Share prices in the Philippine
Stock Exchange closed lower Wednesday despite the United States
Federal Reserve's decision to keep rates steady.
</P>
<P>
The 30-company Phisix, the market's main index, went 5.61
points lower to close at 1,491.31. However, the broader all-shares
index slightly rose 2.21 points to 655.91.
</P>
<P>
Dealers exchanged 549.8 million shares worth some 17.5 million
U.S. dollars on Wednesday against Tuesday's 568 million shares
worth some 11.9 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the steady U.S. rates would not necessarily lift
the market's sentiment over the Philippines' domestic situation,
including the conflict in Mindanao and the unresolved hostage
crisis.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Federal Open Market Committee decided Tuesday to keep
its short-term interest rate target unchanged at 6.50 percent amid
signs of slower economic growth. But the Fed said it may consider
another rate hike in the future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
