<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Opposition Parties Enforce A Half-Day Hartal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh was mostly paralyzed by
a nationwide half-day hartal (destructive strike) Wednesday which
widely disrupted transport services and hit the banking operations.
</P>
<P>
The four-party opposition alliance led by the Bangladesh
Nationalist Party (BNP) enforced the hartal to protest against the
killing of BNP leader and lawyer Habibur Rahman Mondol in the
capital on Sunday by unknown assailants.
</P>
<P>
The Southwestern Regional Road Transport Coordination Committee
has also enforced dawn-to-dusk transport strike in 21 out of 64
districts against the price hike of petroleum products by the
government, which helped the opposition shutdown become more
successful, adding sufferings to the people of that region.
</P>
<P>
Police backed by the para-military Bangladesh Rifles patrolled
the city and manned various posts around the city to prevent
potential violence.
</P>
<P>
There was no report of any disturbance during the shutdown
which started at 6 a.m. and ended at 1 p.m., police sources said.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses said opposition picketers damaged rickshaws during
the shutdown as passengers fled. Police stopped a planned march by
the main opposition BNP, but there was no untoward incident, they
added.
</P>
<P>
Most vehicles stayed off the streets except a large number of
rickshaws, three-wheel motorcycles, taxis and some private and
state-run buses plying in the streets.
</P>
<P>
The government offices worked with slim attendance, while
schools and other educational institutions remained shut, police
sources said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
