<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Putin Meets Dead Sub Crew Relatives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Vladimir Putin
met relatives of the dead crewmen of the sunken nuclear submarine
Kursk Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
According to the Interfax news agency, Putin told the relatives
that he has kept asking the military and submarine designers: "Can
it really be true that nothing more can be done?" "It's impossible
to believe in this. The sorrow is immeasurable and no words of
consolation will suffice. My heart is filled with pain."
</P>
<P>
The questions Putin was asked at the meeting suggested that the
relatives were still refusing to believe that the crew were dead,
Interfax quoted an officer participating in the meeting as saying
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The meeting was very emotional and tense," said the officer.
</P>
<P>
Many speakers at the meeting sharply blamed the military
command. But Putin said it would be possible to punish Northern
Fleet commanders only if their guilt is proved.
</P>
<P>
Although emotions were running high, the relatives of the
Kursk's crew agreed that the Russian rescuers had done everything
they could to save the crew, the source said.
</P>
<P>
On the future life of the dead crewmen's families, including
their children's education at secondary schools and establishments
of higher education and jobs for their widows, Putin said there
will be no apathy in tackling these issues.
</P>
<P>
Most of the relatives were urging the president to continue
efforts to retrieve the bodies of the dead crewmen. Putin and the
Northern Fleet commanders assured that work to retrieve the crew
bodies will be carried through to the end, said the source.
</P>
<P>
Putin, wearing a dark suit and a black shirt without a tie in a
Russian NTV television show of the meeting, spoke in detail about
the rescue operation and about when and how the foreign rescuers
were asked to join in.
</P>
<P>
The governmental commission on the sub accident has announced
that the state would buy an apartment building outside Moscow
where relatives of the dead crewmen might settle.
</P>
<P>
Putin arrived at Russia's Northern Fleet base of Severomorsk
late Tuesday to meet the relatives of the crew in the Kursk
submarine, which went down to the Barents seabed on August 12
during a naval exercise. He returned to Moscow from Severomorsk
Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
Russian Deputy Prime Minister, head of the governmental
commission on the sub accident, Ilya Klebanov, deputy chief of the
presidential staff Alexander Abramov and Commander of the Russian
Navy Vladimir Kuroyedov have remained in Severomorsk to fulfill
Putin's instructions to offer aid to the crew relatives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000823.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
