<HEADLINE> Gold Demand in UAE to Rise 8 Percent This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates' gold
demand is expected to increase by nearly 8 percent by the end of
2000 in light of the attractive prices and the inflow of tourists,
a World Gold Council (WGC) official has said.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, the country's total gold demand was 79.7 tons, said WGC
manager for Gulf states D. V. Pathy, "we will end up this year with
an increase of about 8 percent."
</P>
<P>
Attractive Prices, retailers' marketing promotion activities,
new concepts and the influx of tourists shore up the gold demand,
Pathy said.
</P>
<P>
He quantified the "attractive" prices at 275-280 U.S. dollars
per ounce, also with a room of increase. But he stressed "even the
Price is 300 dollars, we believe consumers' interest in the yellow
metal will be sustained."
</P>
<P>
"we will see an increase in offtake provided prices stabilize at
that lever," so the WGC hope "to wrap up the year with total sales
of about 85 tons," the local English newspaper Gulf News Wednesday
quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
He also estimated that the festival of lights of Hindus, Diwali;
the Muslim fasting month Ramadan; the Eid al-Fitr feast that marks
the end of Ramadan, and the Christmas will also boost the sales.
</P>
<P>
WGC statistics showed that gold sales, including re-exports, in
the Middle East reached 421.3 tons during the first half of 2000, a
9 percent increase from last year's same timescale. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
