<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over 200 HIV Infections Take Place Daily in Zambia  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Addressing a conference on the Challenge of HIV/AIDS in Lusaka
on Tuesday, Sichone said a large number of Zambian families are
keeping more than one orphan whose parents have died of AIDS,
Zambian newspaper, The Post, reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Our people live with the reality of poverty on a day to day
basis. Clearly poverty makes the effective control of HIV/AIDS
difficult, but it too is in part the result of the HIV/AIDS
epidemic," the paper quoted Sichone as saying.
</P>
<P>
Sichone said the country faces a severe external debt burden
that stifles investment in social sectors such as health,
education and the fight against HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
"There exists a preponderance of socio-economic conditions
inimical to the effective prevention and control of HIV/AIDS in
Zambia as in many parts of sub-Saharan Africa," he noted.
</P>
<P>
He was however hopeful that despite the gloomy picture, there
is renewed commitment from the political leadership to fight the
epidemic as evidenced from the setting up of the AIDS council
secretariat in the country.
</P>
<P>
"We continue to have hope because there is an encouraging
decline of HIV infections among the young people in Zambia that
indicates to us that prevention of the spread of HIV is possible,"
Sichone said.
</P>
<P>
However, the United States of America International Development
mission director Allan Reed warned that over the next decade, AIDS
will kill more people in sub-Saharan Africa than in all the wars
of the 20th century combined.
</P>
<P>
"It is a development crisis and we all must mobilize every part
of society to respond, the numbers speak for themselves: 12
million Africans have already died, and another 22 million adults
and one million children are now living with HIV," Reed said.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that half of the youth in Southern Africa who are
now 15 years old will likely die of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
"We have seen important progress in Uganda, Senegal, and also
here in Zambia. In Lusaka, the HIV prevalence among 15-19 year old
dropped from 28 percent in 1993 to 15 percent in 1998, but in
other Zambian age groups, the rate is not changing," Reed said.
</P>
<P>
He said as for the 30,000 children that are born each year to
HIV mothers, programs are needed to reduce vertical transmission.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000823.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Compaq To Build Supercomputer For Military Use </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Compaq Computer Corp. said
Tuesday it won a contract for more than 200 million U.S. dollars
to build a supercomputer for the Department of Energy.
</P>
<P>
Compaq said the computer, called Advanced Strategic Computing
Initiative (ASCI) Q, will have more than 11,968 processors,
allowing it to perform more than 30 trillion operations per second.
That is about 2.5 times as powerful as today's fastest
supercomputer, ASCI White, which was built by IBM for the Energy
Department.
</P>
<P>
ASCI Q will be the size of five basketball courts, or more than
21,000 square feet. The supercomputer is expected to begin working
in early 2002, Compaq said.
</P>
<P>
Press reports said the supercomputer, the largest one being
built under contract today, would be housed at Los Alamos National
Laboratory in New Mexico and used within the National Nuclear
Security Administration's weapons stockpile stewardship program.
The program's work is to certify the safety and reliability of
nuclear weapons without underground nuclear testing.
</P>
<P>
John A. Gordon, the chief of the nuclear security agency, said
the weapons reliability program has historically required the
fastest computers available and the contract announced Tuesday
would accelerate the evolution of technical computing.
</P>
<P>
Experts believe that ASCI Q will be composed of linked
AlphaServers, Compaq's brand of computers for heavy-duty corporate
tasks. The highly visible deal strengthens Compaq in this market,
where it competes with IBM and Sun Microsystems, among others.
</P>
<P>
Compaq scored another victory early this month, when it was
selected to build and manage the world's largest nonmilitary
supercomputer. The Pittsburgh Supercomputing Center will operate
the computer for the National Science Foundation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000823.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Religious Delegation Visits U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 22 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese religious leaders
delegation began its visit to the United States Tuesday with
Bishop of the Chinese Catholic Church Michael Fu Tieshan
delivering a speech at the University of California in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Fu, chairman of the China Catholicism
Association and head of the delegation,dealt with the situation of
religions in China, saying that religions in China are entering a
"golden age."
</P>
<P>
He said that there are more than 100 million religious
followers in China, more than 85,000 places of worship and 3,000
religious communities with 30,000 clergy to serve spiritual needs
of their followers.
</P>
<P>
Of the top five religions, Buddhism, the most influential, has
a history of 2,000 years in China,Taoism, native to the country,
has a history of more than 1,700 years. Islam was introduced to
China in the seventh century. Catholicism and Protestantism boomed
in China with the humiliating Opium War in the 1840s, but they
still have 4 million and 10 million followers in China today.
</P>
<P>
It is stipulated by law that Chinese citizens may freely choose
and express their religious beliefs and make clear their religious
affiliations, Fu told the meeting of 100 religious leaders in
California and scholars.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese religious leaders delegation, the first of its kind
to visit abroad, is to attend the Millennium World Peace Summit of
religious and spiritual leaders, which is to be held in the United
Nations headquarters later this month.
</P>
<P>
Apart from Fu, other members of the delegation are President of
China's Christian Council Dr. Han Wenzao, Taoist master Min
Zhiting, Islamic Akhund Chen Guangyuan, Living Buddha Jamyang
Losang Jigme Tubdain Qoigyi Nyima, Buddhist master Sheng Hui, and
Rev. Ms Cao Shengjie.  
</P>
</TEXT>
