<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, August 23 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- The Serbian government Tuesday decided to cut
agricultural taxes in a bid to alleviate the negative impacts of
the month-long heat wave on farmers and agricultural enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The move will exempt farmers from the land revenue tax,
property tax and part of property taxes of the agricultural
production by agricultural enterprises, the Yugoslav news agency
Tanjug reported. Persisting high temperatures and severe drought
have hit Yugoslavia for nearly a month, causing inconveniences to
people's daily life and affecting agricultural production. (
Belgrade-Agriculture-Duty)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- Vietnam Airline (VA) will resume direct air flights
from Hanoi to Seoul and from Ho Chi Minh City to Seoul in October
this year, the Construction and Transportation Ministry said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese airline, which suspended the direct flights in
early 1998 after Southeastern and Eastern Asia was hit by an
economic crisis, will operate direct air routes between Seoul and
Hanoi three times a week and between Seoul and Ho Chi Minh City
five times a week. At present, South Korea's Korean Air and Asiana
Airlines each operate five direct flights per week between Seoul
and Ho Chi Minh City. (Vietnam-Flights-Seoul)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- Visiting Japanese Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori said
here on Wednesday he would give further impetus to Indo-Japan
relations and make them much closer.
</P>
<P>
"I will like to make India-Japan relations much better than
what they are now," said Mori after he was accorded a ceremonial
welcome at the presidential place here Wednesday morning. Mori,
who arrived here Tuesday evening for a three-day official visit
from Bangalore, 2,000 kilometers south of here, is scheduled to
hold wide-ranging talks later Wednesday with his Indian
counterpart Atal Bihari Vajpayee on regional, international and
issues of mutual concern, a high-ranking Indian official said. (
India-Japan-Mori) 
</P>
