<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Popov to Meet Klim in Melbourne Pre-Olympic Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Russian swimming czar Alex
Popov will race against Australia's Michael Klim in a pre-Olympic
100 meters freestyle clash in Melbourne this weekend, Australian
sports officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The pair are ranked No.1 and No.2 in the world rankings in the
prestigious men's sprint event going into next month's Sydney
Games.
</P>
<P>
Popov will contest in both 50m and 100m freestyle events at the
Melbourne grand prix, the Australian Olympic team's last
competition before the Sydney Games.
</P>
<P>
A win in Melbourne would give the victor a psychological edge
going into the Olympics, they said.
</P>
<P>
The 100m event will be one of the most tightly fought of the
weekend, with Australian world numberfive Chris Fydler and
talented Algerian swimmer Salim Illes also competing.
</P>
<P>
Klim pulled out of the Games' 200m freestyle - one of his world
championship gold medal events - after the Olympic trials in May
to concentrate on the 100m freestyle and butterfly in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
But Popov, who recently broke the world 50m freestyle record at
the Russian trials, won't give up the gold medal easily.
</P>
<P>
He's won the 50 and 100m freestyle double at the last two
Olympics and has a chance in Sydney to become the first male
swimmer in history to "do a Dawn."
</P>
<P>
Australia's Dawn Fraser was the first swimmer to win the same
Olympic event three-times when she won the 100m freestyle during
the span from 1956-1964.
</P>
<P>
It's a feat only equaled by Hungarian Krisztina Egerszegi who
won the 200m backstroke between 1988 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
Popov has two chances to do it in Sydney, both before Australia
's Kieren Perkins goes for the 1500m freestyle triple on September
23 - the last day of swimming competition.
</P>
<P>
The Melbourne grand prix has attracted swimmers from Britain,
South Africa, Algeria, Angola, Malaysia, Fiji, Singapore, Papua
New Guinea and Nigeria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
