<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sydney Olympic Organizers Put More Tickets for Sale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Sydney Olympic organisers
Wednesday abandoned their premium tickets scheme and put 75,000
new A category tickets on sale to the general public.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the decision, Olympics Minister Michael Knight said
the scheme to sell top tickets to the rich had soured public
enthusiasm for the Games.
</P>
<P>
Knight said he was personally given the responsibility to
decide on a superticket premium scheme by the Sydney Organizing
Committee for the Olympic Games (SOCOG) board, which had the
blessing of the International Olympic Committee.
</P>
<P>
"But in the end, I've decided not to do it," he told ABC radio.
</P>
<P>
"When I think back to the way in which the premium ticket
packages soured the whole public feeling about ticketing, I don't
want to see that happen again," he said.
</P>
<P>
Knight said the 75,000 A category tickets kept aside from last
year's disastrous original premium tickets program would go on
public sale at list price.
</P>
<P>
"We could get a few extra million out of it, but right now,
when enthusiasm's building, when (we) ... have re-established a
credible ticket selling proposal, I don't want to place that in
jeopardy," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It's a false economy and I really want to get those tickets
out to average Australians," he added.
</P>
<P>
Knight said 13,700 artistic gymnastics tickets, around 13,000
basketball finals tickets and the 3,000 tickets to the men's gold
medal soccer matches would be available from next Tuesday, only
through box offices and the call center. 
</P>
</TEXT>
