<HEADLINE> Sydney Olympic Drug Testing Blitz Starts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 23 (Xinhua) -- An Australian Sports Drug
Agency (ASDA) spokeswoman said here on Wednesday the largest drug
testing program in the 104-year history of the Olympics had been
launched.
</P>
<P>
She said at least 2000 tests under three programs run by ASDA,
the International Olympic Committee and the World Anti-Doping
Agency (WADA) would be conducted before the Games begin on
September 15.
</P>
<P>
"Without a doubt, there's more tests in the leadup to these
Games than ever before," the spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
"If someone's taking drugs ... I think they're taking a big
risk," she said.
</P>
<P>
It's reported that drug testing officials took urine samples
from Dutch world record breaking swimmer Inge De Bruin soon after
she arrived in Australia earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
De Bruin has set eight world swimming records in the past four
months.
</P>
<P>
But the spokeswoman refused to confirm the Dutch team had been
asked to supply samples.
</P>
<P>
Testing officials are expected in Brisbane in Australia's
Queensland state next week where the high profile United States
swimmers will train, reports said.
</P>
<P>
And some Australian swimmers were also targeted during their
recent training camp at Caloundra, on the Queensland state's
Sunshine Coast. 
</P>
</TEXT>
