<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Turkish Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading Turkish newspapers on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Daily News:
</P>
<P>
-- The body of former Azeri President Abulfaz Elchibey, who died
at Ankara's GATA Hospital on Tuesday morning, was sent to
Azerbaijan after a state ceremony at Ankara's Esenboga Airport the
same day.
</P>
<P>
Turkish soldiers carried the coffin to the plane after attendees
observed a minute of respect for Elchibey.
</P>
<P>
Turkish State Minister Abdulhaluk Cay said that Elchibey held a
special place in the history of Azerbaijan, a Turkish ally in the
Caucasus, adding that he had struggled for the independence of
Azerbaijan.
</P>
<P>
For the past two months, Elchibey had been undergoing treatment
in Ankara for prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
Elchibey was Azerbaijan's first democratically elected president
following the country's independence in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Hurriyet:
</P>
<P>
-- Greece will lift the daily visa application for Turkish
tourists who want to visit the Aegean islands of Greece in summer.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made after a meeting between Greek Foreign
Minister George Papandreou and Turkish Public Order Minister
Michalis Chrysochoidis.
</P>
<P>
But Greece will request tourism agencies to inform it about the
number of tourists who will visit the islands one day in advance to
prevent illegal immigration.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that the move was a step forward in the
improvement of Turco-Greek bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Milliyet:
</P>
<P>
-- The skeletons of Byzantine soldiers, who were killed by the
armies of Crusaders, were found in five separate mass graves during
the ongoing archaeological excavations in Iznik township of western
Bursa province in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Archaeologist Bedri Yalman, chief of the team which carries out
the excavations on behalf of Turkish Cultural Ministry, said on
Tuesday that they made very important findings during the
excavations that started in 1980.
</P>
<P>
Historians said that Byzantine Emperor Theodos Laskaris withdrew
to Iznik upon this development and continued his administration
here.
</P>
<P>
Crusaders felt uneasy over this and staged attacks on Iznik.
Clashes occurred between the sides. As a result, dead bodies of the
Byzantine soldiers could not be sent away as the city was besieged,
and they were buried in the town.
</P>
<P>
Yenibinyil:
</P>
<P>
-- Ankara was shaken by a 4.3-magnitude earthquake which took
place at 14:42 local time (1142 GMT) on Tuesday. No serious damage
and casualties were reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
