<HEADLINE> New Zealand Unveils Military Spending Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand government
announced here Wednesday it is spending 735 million NZ dollars (
about 330 million U.S. dollars) on new armored vehicles and radios,
but put an upgrade of the Air Force's Orion aircraft on hold.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Mark Burton formally announced the government'
s decision in the House Wednesday afternoon, saying the government
would spend 611 million NZ dollars (about 275 million U.S. dollars)
over the next four years on 105 Canadian Lav3 armored vehicles for
the Army and 124 million NZ dollars (about 55 million U.S. dollars)
over two years on 1,835 new VHF and handheld radios for the Army
and Air Force.
</P>
<P>
He also said the proposed upgrade of the airforce's six P-3
Orions has been abandoned after price tag climbed to over 550
million NZ dollars (about 248 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The defense minister announced Hobsonville Air Base in Auckland
is to be closed and its functions realigned at some other bases.
</P>
<P>
The government is concentrating "defense resources in areas
where they are most needed," Burton said in the House. 
</P>
</TEXT>
