<HEADLINE> New Zealand Dissatisfied by Australia's Delay in Lifting Apple Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 23 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand has not ruled out
taking Australia to the World Trade Organization over a long-
standing apple ban dispute, according to Television New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
Australia has been reviewing a 78-year ban on New Zealand
apples to keep out the plant disease fireblight, although somewhat
slowly.
</P>
<P>
The New Zealand government and apple industry have been growing
increasingly impatient at the delay in announcing the outcome of
the review of the ban. A risk assessment carried out by the
Australian Quarantine Service was due out 10 months ago.
</P>
<P>
The review's release has been postponed four times and the
latest release date for the review is the end of next month.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand Agriculture and Trade Negotiations Minister Jim
Sutton Wednesday was quoted as saying if the dispute is not
resolved soon, he would consider taking a complaint against
Australia to the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
"There is a general expectation both here and in Australia that
the review will recommend relaxing the ban, at least to allow
imports of New Zealand apples from fireblight free areas," Sutton
said.
</P>
<P>
He said if that is the outcome, he is prepared to wait a little
longer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
