<HEADLINE> New Zealand Dollar Sinking to All-Time Low Against USD </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand dollar has
sunk to all-time low against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
It fell below 44 U.S. cents for the first time in more than 15
years Wednesday, trading at 43.47 U.S. cents after losing 1.53 U.S.
cents overnight.
</P>
<P>
The last lowest record for the New Zealand dollar was at 43.70
U.S. cents in 1985.
</P>
<P>
"The latest drubbing overnight was not sparked by an individual
event. Rather, the strength of the U.S. dollar keeps sucking
investors away from all other currencies, while the New Zealand
dollar's long-time vulnerabilities leave it even more exposed,"
the Evening Post said.
</P>
<P>
"A large current account deficit, uncertainty about interest
rate prospects and slipping support for the government are all
weighing on it," the Wellington-based newspaper said. 
</P>
