<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Health Ministers of South-East Asian Countries Meet in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The 18th meeting of health
ministers of the countries of the WHO South-East Asia Region (SEAR)
kicked off here Wednesday .
</P>
<P>
The health ministers will discuss during the three-day meeting
issues such as rationalizing WHO (World Health Organization)
resources to inter-countries counterparts, health sector reforms,
HIV/AIDS problems, as well as deliberating on new strategies for
strengthening inter-country collaborations in the region.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the inaugural ceremony, Dr. Uton Muchtar Rafei,
Regional Director of WHO, said that at the threshold of the 21st
century, the health sectors of the region are facing both
challenges and opportunities.
</P>
<P>
"Environmental degradation, lack of safe drinking water and
basic sanitation for millions of people will continue to be
serious challenges in the coming century," said Rafei.
</P>
<P>
"Widespread poverty, illiteracy, malnutrition, and the
generally low status of women hamper the health development in the
region, while the ever-increasing population, rapid and unplanned
urbanization and industrialization compound the situation," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Rafei said, however, there are great opportunities "for us to
seize them and meet the challenges head on".
</P>
<P>
"I am confident that this meeting will provide an opportunity
to reinforce the common bonds of friendship and cooperation in our
countries, and will lead to renewed commitment, collective self-
reliance and regional solidarity in health development," Rafei
said.
</P>
<P>
Health ministers of all SEAR countries except Sri Lanka --
Bangladesh, Bhutan, the Democratic People's Republic of Korea,
India, Indonesia, Maldives, Myanmar, Nepal, and Thailand -- are
participating in the meeting, which is jointly organized by the
Nepali Health Ministry and WHO. Sri Lanka is being represented by
its Additional Health Secretary as an observer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
