<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nike Aims to Double Women's Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Nike Inc., the world's No. 1
company for sports shoes, claimed Tuesday to have formed a unit
specifically for designing and selling products for women, aiming
to double its share of the market in two years.
</P>
<P>
Nike said its women's apparel sectors located in department
stores across the United States have already achieved good
performance. Women's retail sales both in Japan and through its
female-oriented Web site in Hong Kong have also been encouraging.
</P>
<P>
"Nike's women's business is one of our major growth
accelerators in the U.S. and internationally, making it one of our
company's top priorities," Nike's chief executive, Philip Knight,
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Nike appointed Clare Hamill, who formerly headed Nike's
equipment division, to lead the new women's business as vice
president, effective immediately.
</P>
<P>
Hamill, who has been with Nike since 1981, said the company
planned to double or triple its investments in nearly all areas of
the women's business, including designing, advertising, and
retailing.
</P>
<P>
"Nike has always demonstrated leadership in women's products,
but we're going to make even greater strides in acting and
thinking like a women's company," Hamill said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Currently, women's apparel and footwear make up about 20
percent of Nike's total sales of 25 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Beaverton, Ore.-based Nike sees the booming popularity of
women's sports -- highlighted by the success of the women's
professional basketball and the U.S. women's national soccer team -
- as a prime opportunity to bolster its top line.
</P>
<P>
But Nike's share price dropped almost 12 percent after the
announcement, though analysts said the decline had little to do
with the company's decision to step up its marketing to women.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Tuesday morning, a J.P. Morgan analyst lowered her
estimate of the company's U.S. footwear sales growth, citing the
recent overall sluggishness in U.S. retail sales. 
</P>
</TEXT>
