<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Closes More Land to Recreational Use </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Dangerous wildfires and a
shortage of firefighters have led U.S. federal authorities to
close more Western forests and grassland to camping, tourism and
other recreational use effective early Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Bureau of Land Management Tuesday said it is ordering
another 1.3 million acres of the land it controls in western and
central Montana closed to the public.
</P>
<P>
Last week, 6 million to 8 million acres of state, private,
tribal and federal land were closed to prevent additional fires
and to reduce the chance that people could be trapped by wildfires.
</P>
<P>
And Montana Gov. Marc Racicot was expected Wednesday to close
state grasslands and forests to campers, hikers and fishermen in
16 counties.
</P>
<P>
The National Interagency Fire Center in Idaho said Tuesday that
79 fires were burning on 1.4 million acres of land in Arizona,
California, Idaho, Montana, Nevada, Oklahoma, Texas, Utah and
Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, fires have consumed some 5.7 million acres --
more than double the 10-year average and an area bigger than the
state of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
The hardest hit states remain Idaho and Montana, where a
combined 56 fires are burning more than 1.2 million acres in
mostly steep, rugged terrain that is difficult to reach.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Montana had 29 large fires on 613,000 acres, the
fire center reported. More than a third of the blackened land lay
in the Bitterroot Valley of southwestern Montana.
</P>
<P>
Manpower remained in short supply Tuesday, as firefighters
struggled against the massive host of wildfires. The shortage has
affected the way agencies approach the blazes.
</P>
<P>
In Idaho, the nation's largest wildfire continued to devour the
Salmon-Challis National Forest. The fire had consumed about 159,
000 acres, but was about one-third contained.
</P>
<P>
Almost 1,600 firefighters were fighting the blaze, aided by 16
helicopters and 58 fire engines.
</P>
<P>
An army battalion from Ft. Campbell, Ky., was also expected to
reinforce Montana firefighters later this week, followed a few
days later by another contingent from Fort Bragg, N.C.
</P>
<P>
They will join about 2,900 U.S. military, National Guard and
Reserve troops already aiding the some 20,000 weary firefighters
working to contain the blazes.
</P>
<P>
Firefighters from Canada, Mexico and as far away as Australia
and New Zealand are also battling the fires expected to burn
through at least September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000823.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
