<HEADLINE> Thailand Raises Forecast Number of Tourist Arrivals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Foreign tourist arrivals in
Thailand during the first five months of this year totaled 3.99
million, up 11.27 percent from the corresponding period last year,
prompting the Tourism Authority of Thailand (TAT) to revise its
prediction for the year upwards to 9.12 million visitors.
</P>
<P>
"If this trend continues, Thailand should be able to end the
year with a total of 9.12 million international arrivals, well
above the estimated 8.8 million," a TAT report said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It said that the TAT also expect the upcoming Sydney Olympic
Games, will encourage pre- and post-Olympics stopovers to Thailand
during September and October.
</P>
<P>
According to TAT figures, among the foreign tourists arrived in
Thailand in the first five months, East Asia accounted for 2.37
million arrivals; Europe 983,875; North America 252,410; South
Asia 130,916; Oceania 142,635; the Middle East 69,985; and Africa
30,910 visitors.
</P>
<P>
On the outbound front, the number of Thais traveling abroad
totaled 841,983 during January to May, a 16-percent increase over
the same period in 1999. Their average length of stay overseas was
11.28 days, the report said.
</P>
<P>
In the same period, the number of foreign expatriates living in
Thailand who traveled abroad totaled 16,052 people, an 18.29-
percent increase over the corresponding period last year, it said.
</P>
</TEXT>
