<HEADLINE> Thai Gov't to Set up Funds to Relieve Oil Price Pressure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Recent oil-price hikes have hit these two sectors hardest,
government spokesman Akapol Sorasuchart was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The government also decided to ensure state-owned transport and
bus companies keeping fares at current levels.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet has instructed the State Railways of Thailand to
keep its third-class fares at their current level. The Bangkok
Mass Transit Authority and the Transport Corporation were also
asked to maintain their current fares.
</P>
<P>
The Express Transportation Organization of Thailand, another
state-owned enterprise managed by the transport and communications
ministry, was also told not to increase fares.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has been instructed to establish a special fund to
help ease the woes of private transport businesses.
</P>
<P>
But private operators of inter-provincial buses will be allowed
to increase their fares to accommodate increased costs.
</P>
<P>
The government also proposed the taxis be converted to run on
natural gas, promising to finance taxi modifications, including
installation of a gas tank in each vehicle.
</P>
<P>
However, the government ruled out tax measures as a means of
easing fuel costs, saying that reducing oil taxes might undermine
the its monetary austerity policy and encourage increased petrol
consumption, which will adversely affect the economy in the long
run. 
</P>
