<DOCNO> XIE20000823.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Home to 4,500 Elephants: Census </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's elephant population
ranges from 4,000 to 4,500, some 1,500 more than earlier estimate,
according to the latest census taken by the Department of Wildlife
Conservation.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Director of Wildlife Conservation Nandana Attapattu was
quoted by the official Daily News as saying on Wednesday that an
earlier survey, which was not conducted on a proper basis, had
inaccurately estimated the elephant population at between 2,500
and 3,000.
</P>
<P>
He said that elephants were being killed in large numbers due
to human encroachment, poaching and the destruction of their
habitat because of the civil war in which rebels are fighting for
a homeland for the minority Tamils in the country's north and east
since 1983.
</P>
<P>
In 1970-1980 about 50 elephants were shot or captured annually.
Later in 1980-1990 about 50 more were shot dead by farmers yearly
to protect their crops. At present it is estimated that there are
about 150 elephant deaths per year.
</P>
<P>
In 1948 when Sri Lanka gained independence, there were more
than 20,000 elephants in the country which are viewed as national
treasures protected under law.
</P>
<P>
According to the census, there are about 226 domestic elephants
in the country which had been reduced due to the lack of breeding
facilities. Between 1946 and 2000 domestic elephant births were
only seven in addition to the 17 births recorded at the Pinnawela
Elephant Orphanage under captive breeding. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000823.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar to Use Japanese Seismographs in Earthquake Forecasting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar will use Japanese-made
high-intensity seismographs in forecasting earthquake in the
country, official newspaper The New Light of Myanmar reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The seismographs, presented by the Oyo Corporation of Japan,
will be installed and put into services in 10 major cities of
Myanmar --Yangon, Mandalay, Sittway, Myitkyina, Monywa, Meihtila,
Bagan,Maubin, Bago and Thayawaddy.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Myanmar will hold an international workshop on
network of high-intensity earthquake next month to seek up-to-date
technology in forecasting earthquake, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar has planned a new setup of its Meteorological and
Hydrological Department to serve more effectively in mitigating
the adverse effects of natural disasters, weather and climate on
human health.
</P>
<P>
The new setup includes building of more related stations and
forecasting offices and reinforcement of staff members.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, Myanmar has established 34
new meteorological and hydrological stations in the past decade,
bringing the total number of such stations to 130. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000823.0237 </DOCNO>
