<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clash Kills Three in Irian Jaya, Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Three civilians have been killed
and nine others injured during a clash between police and
separatists in Irian Jaya province, Indonesia, the Jakarta Post
daily reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The clash broke out at about 8:30 local time on Tuesday, after
some 500 supporters of the Free Papua Organization (OPM) hoisted
the separatist flag outside a church in the coastal oil town of
Sorong.
</P>
<P>
Official sources were quoted as saying that 38 civilians have
been detained following the incident.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Irian Jaya Police Chief Senior Superintendent Thamrin
Simandjuntak said five policemen were badly injured after being
stabbed with machetes, arrows and spears by separatists.
</P>
<P>
He said the policemen were met by a spray of arrows and spears,
and they retaliated by opening fire with rubber bullets.
</P>
<P>
Irian Jaya was incorporated into Indonesia in 1963, after heavy
diplomatic pressure on the Netherlands, the country's former
colonial ruler. In 1969, a U.N.-run plebiscite was held among
local leaders, which resulted in a vote to join Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The violence in Sorong came a day after separatist leaders
threatened to wage an all-out war against Jakarta if their calls
for independence remained unheeded.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Indonesian President Abdurrahman Wahid told
the People's Consultative Assembly that Irian Jaya would be
accorded broad autonomy before the end of the year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
