<HEADLINE> Mexico Receives More Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Mexico attracted 6.676
billion U.S. dollars of direct foreign investment (DFI) in the
first half of this year, up 22.1 percent over the same period in
1999, the Secretariat of Trade said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Canada stay as the main source of DFI
with 75.4 percent, followed by the European Union 17.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Secretariat said that since the North American Free Trade
Agreement (NAFTA) went into force in January 1994, DFI has kept
flowing into Mexico. The United States, Canada and Mexico are
signatories of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
The Secretariat expected that DFI from the EU will increase
after the free trade treaty between the two sides went into effect
in July.  
</P>
