<HEADLINE> Serbian Government Cuts Agricultural Taxes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The Serbian government Tuesday
decided to cut agricultural taxes in a bid to alleviate the
negative impacts of the month-long heat wave on farmers and
agricultural enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The move will exempt farmers from the land revenue tax,
property tax and part of property taxes of the agricultural
production by agricultural enterprises, the Yugoslav news agency
Tanjug reported.
</P>
<P>
Persisting high temperatures and severe drought have hit
Yugoslavia for nearly a month, causing inconveniences to people's
daily life and affecting agricultural production.
</P>
<P>
In Belgrade, the temperature reached 40 degrees centigrade on
Tuesday, the highest recorded in the city in 54 years.
</P>
<P>
Belgrade and many other cities have taken measures to limit
water supplies.  
</P>
