<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia's External Debt Rockets in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOGOTA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Colombia's external debt exceeded
34.4 billion U.S. dollars in June, equivalent to 40 percent of the
country's gross domestic product GDP), the Central Bank of the
Republic said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Economists attributed the quick rise of Colombia's foreign debt
to the tax crisis that obliged the government to seek funds on the
more costly outside market.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that when a country's international debts amount
to over 25 percent of its GDP, it has crossed the indebtedness
threshold, so Colombia's situation is alarming.
</P>
<P>
Debt servicing went up to 6.696 billion dollars in 1999,
accounting for 60 percent of Colombia's export earnings of that
year.
</P>
<P>
While Colombia is facing political and economic instability,
banks have considered investing in Colombia as highly risky.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
