<HEADLINE> Consumer Goods Industry Attracts Foreign Investors in Romania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The consumer goods industry in
Romania attracts more and more foreign investors, the official
Rompres news agency reported Wednesday by citing a study of an
international consultancy company.
</P>
<P>
According to the study by the Roland Berger and Partners
international consultancy company, the Romanian consumer goods
market amounts to about 7 billion U.S. dollars a year, with bakery
products holding 17 percent of the market; tobacco, 16 percent;
and milk products, 15 percent. Coffee and beer hold 10 percent of
the market each while soft drinks and wine hold 7 percent each.
</P>
<P>
The importance of the consumer goods market has determined the
upward trend of other domains too, especially in distribution and
transport. Many retail selling networks and supermarkets as well
as cash and carry networks appeared in quite a short time.
Companies such as Interbrands, First Romanian Distribution,
Overseas and Cosmos appeared.
</P>
<P>
The consumer goods industry has also influenced the advertising
industry, with the consumer goods producers spending over 300
million U.S. dollars on advertising, about three-quarters of the
total expenditures for advertising in the country. As a result,
the advertising sector has rapidly developed by 50 percent
annually. 
</P>
</TEXT>
