<HEADLINE> U.S. Delivers Last Check for Canal Profits to Panama </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, August 23 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Ambassador to Panama
Simon Ferro delivered Wednesday to Panamanian President Mireya
Moscoso the last check for Canal profits obtained during the U.S.
administration of the waterway.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. ambassador said that the check, issued by the U.S.
Treasury, is for 6,666,141 dollars and 39 cents and will be made
to the Panamanian National Treasury.
</P>
<P>
"This is the last of a series of payments of profits from the
United States to the Panamanian government and represents the
completion of an excellent working relationship between the United
States and Panama, based on the good will and cooperation at all
levels," said Ferro.
</P>
<P>
The check corresponds to the financial auditing made by the old
Panama Canal Commission (PCC) during the first quarter of this
fiscal year, which includes operations between October 1, 1999 to
September 30, 2000.
</P>
<P>
The PCC, an agency of the U.S. federal government, entered
history with the reversion of the Panama Canal, which occurred on
December 31, 1999, according to the Torrijos-Carter Treaties
signed in 1977.
</P>
<P>
The delivery of the check was made during the planting of more
than 500 seedlings of native species in the east of the Culebra
Cut, the narrowest part of the Canal of Panama, by 300 children,
to continue commemorating the 86th anniversary of the waterway.
</P>
<P>
President Mireya Moscoso said it is very important for the
Panamanian government to support the projects of the Panama Canal
Authority, the entity that replaces the PCC to take charge of the
canal operation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
