<HEADLINE> Somalis Caught by Presidential Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Most Somalis were drawn before
a TV or radio on Thursday as the country's presidential candidates
deliver speeches campaigning for the forthcoming elections to be
held on Sunday in Arta, Djibouti, where a peace conference has
been held to find a central government for the Somalis.
</P>
<P>
In the capital Mogadishu, streets were empty and many of the
business activities closed down while thousands of people either
watched TV or listened to the radio, both of which carried a live
coverage of the presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
In some areas, loudspeakers have been mounted on top of the
trees as the campaign continued.
</P>
<P>
During the speeches, four out of the 29 candidates officially
withdrawn from their desire to continue running for the presidency
of Somalia, leaving room for the other 25 still contesting for the
post.
</P>
<P>
Each of the 25 candidates delivered a seven-minute speech
spelling out his way of governance in the future. All of them
promised to rescue the country out of the current political and
social turmoil and pave the way for economic development.
</P>
<P>
Among the most interesting candidates was a man who pledged
that he would dig 63 oil wells, build up over 40 large factories,
dig more than 300 water wells and make use of most of the rivers
and coastal lands for fishing and settling down Somalia's large
nomadic societies along the sea sides and river banks.
</P>
<P>
The man, named Ibrahim Hassan Jumaleh, is not a well known man
in Somalia's recent politics, but he made the Somalis laugh to the
deepest of their hearts.
</P>
<P>
"I would not work for the faction leaders if I could get
employment in any of those oil wells," said a delighted gunman who
held a small FM radio to his ear near Bakara market.
</P>
<P>
Many people have applauded for Abdiqasim Salad Hassan, Somalia'
s former interior minister, who made his speech a very much
contemporary and carefully written one. He pledged a full recovery
in economy by choosing the market-oriented policy, good
international relation and enhancement of education for Somali
children.
</P>
<P>
Hassan also vowed for democracy, saying the Islamic laws will
all the time remain the points of reference.
</P>
<P>
Somalia's former finance minister Mohamed Sheikh Osman and
faction leader Ali Mahdi Mohamed have also been among the figures
who have attracted some people.
</P>
<P>
Following the speeches on Thursday, the candidates will run for
the presidency in an election Friday. According to Speaker
Abdulahi Deerow Issack of the transitional parliament, each of the
parliamentarians will cast his/her vote in a secret ballot
beginning from 15:30 local time (1230GMT).
</P>
<P>
No matter how long the voting takes, the exercise will be non-
stop until the final decision is made and the president of Somalia
is announced for the first time after ten years of anarchy and
lawlessness, Issack said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
