<HEADLINE> UNIDO to Offer 1 Million U.S. Dollars to Zimbabwe's Flower Growers  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Industrial
Development Organization (UNIDO) has approved a facility with a
total value of 1 million U.S. dollars to assist Zimbabwe's flower
growers for pilot project using steam instead of chemicals to
eradicate insects in the soil, a Zimbabwean official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Chief Executive of the Export Flower Growers Association of
Zimbabwe Mary Dunphy told the Zimbabwe News Agency that the first
boiler for this four-year project will arrive in the country in
January next year and the 1 million U.S. dollars will cover the
cost of the boilers and the training of people who will be
involved in the project.
</P>
<P>
Instead of going on using chemicals, the growers now want to
adopt the use of steam as a soil fumigant ahead of the set
schedules to phase out the use of chemicals by the year 2015 as
stipulated in the Montreal Protocol.
</P>
<P>
She said the technology had been used in Colombia and had
proved a success if done together with good compositing techniques
and good management techniques.
</P>
<P>
A Colombian consultant was sent to Zimbabwe by UNIDO recently
and gave growers an insight into the production of cut flowers
using steam as a fumigant.
</P>
<P>
Floriculture has been a success in Zimbabwe, which earns the
country millions of dollars in foreign currency.
</P>
<P>
During the 1999/2000 season, the sector exported 20,200 tons of
flower which was a 20 percent increase from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The association which is comprised of more than 280 flower
growers has exported most of its flowers to the European Union and
the Netherlands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
