<HEADLINE> Zambia Calls for More International Support for Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Zambian Home Affairs Minister
Peter Machungwa Thursday appealed for more support from
international institutions to accommodate a large number of
refugees in the country.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) and
the World Food Program (WFP) should increase food supplies to the
refugees in various camps in Zambia if law and order is to be
maintained in those camps, Machungwa said during a meeting with
visiting UNHCR regional director to Southern Africa Ilunga Ngandu.
</P>
<P>
Machungwa noted that due to inadequate food supplies riots have
been reported in some of the camps causing a serious security risk
to both the locals and the refugees, adding that as a result some
local chiefs have called on the government to remove the refugees
from their areas.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the minister deplored the discrepancies in the
treatment of African refugees in comparison with refugees in other
parts of the world and called for equal refugee treatment
regardless of color or creed.
</P>
<P>
Ilunga Ngandu echoed Machungwa's call, saying Zambia needs more
international support in its efforts to provide a safe-haven for
refugees fleeing armed conflict and persecution.
</P>
<P>
There are over 200,000 refugees in Zambia mainly from Angola,
the Democratic Republic of the Congo, Burundi, Somalia and Rwanda.
</P>
</TEXT>
