<HEADLINE> S. African Police Chief Lobbys for Firearms Control Bill  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Proposals in the Firearms
Control Bill would greatly enhance the effectiveness of crime-
fighting operations undertaken by the South African Police Service
(SAPS), national police Commissioner Jackie Selebi said on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Among other things, they would significantly strengthen the
SAPS' ability to regulate and control both legally and illegally
possessed firearms, Selebi said.
</P>
<P>
Briefing the National Assembly's safety and security committee,
Selebi said provisions in the bill would result in fewer guns
finding their way out of legal hands and into illegal ones.
</P>
<P>
The draft legislation made a clear distinction between what was
legal and what was not, gave the police improved powers of search
and seizure and paved the way for more effective policing.
</P>
<P>
Rigorously implemented and appropriately supported by other
mechanisms, the bill represented a major tool, essential in the
fight against violent crime, the police chief said.
</P>
<P>
The police saw the reduction and ultimate eradication of
illegal firearms as a priority, he said.
</P>
<P>
Selebi and various members of his senior management team
rejected allegations by some organizations that the bill would
prove impossible to implement and cost too much.
</P>
<P>
"In response to repeated concerns regarding implementation and
resources, it is important to note that we have, wherever possible,
addressed requirements in the bill in a flexible way so that there
is a less expensive or taxing alternative to the ideal," he said.
</P>
<P>
South Africans suffered the effects of widespread crime and
rejection of the law every day. 
</P>
