<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Former South African
president Nelson Mandela said on Thursday he did not have the
slightest doubt that all parties involved in Burundi's seven-year
civil war would sign a peace deal on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters in his Johannesburg office, Mandela said
the parties were committed to peace and "they have not
disappointed me so far".
</P>
<P>
Mandela, chief mediator for Burundi peace talks, will travel to
the Tanzanian town of Arusha on Saturday for Monday's signing
ceremony which will also be witnessed by U.S. President Bill
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
The run-up to the signing has been marked by an increase in
hostilities in Burundi and growing opposition to the draft text of
the deal.
</P>
<P>
However, Mandela said he was confident that the peace deal
would be signed as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
"There is no question whatsoever," he said. "The overwhelming
majority of parties and I believe every party is going to sign."
</P>
<P>
On whether the parties were genuinely committed to peace,
Mandela said: "We are dealing with a highly complicated political
issue. There are 19 political parties and they differ on almost
every point . But nevertheless we have persuaded them to agree to
the unanimous resolution in which they committed themselves to
signing." 
