<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola's Economic Growth Registers at 6.5 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Angola has seen an average
economic growth rate of 6.5 percent during the last five years, an
official of the International Monetary Fund (IMF) was quoted as
saying here on Thursday by the official news agency Angop.
</P>
<P>
Jose Pedro de Morais, who made the statement in Luanda when
addressing a seminar on the role of planning and integrated
management for developing the Angolan economy, said that evolution
of the gross domestic product (GDP) was largely determined by the
consequences of the war which erupted in late 1992. In 1996, four
years after the recrudescence of the Angolan civil war, the GDP
went back to the level of the prewar 1992, estimated at eight
billion U.S.dollars.
</P>
<P>
In his opinion, the recovery was insufficient to restore the
loss of incomes by the population during the 10 years previous to
1995. In the last five years, the public expenditures
systematically exceeded the revenues, showing a fiscal deficit of
between 29 and 13 percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
This implies needs for very significant funding into the public
sector, said the IMF official. Pedro de Morais noted that the
Angolan National Bank (BNA) has been making an enormous effort to
try to stabilize the monetary aggregates and the inflation, adding
that if everything goes on well, a supplementary drop in inflation
of up to two digits is expected next year, after reforms were
successfully introduced into the monetary market plus the
liberalization of the interest rates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
