<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Scholar Urges to Reform AIDS Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 24 (Xinhua) -- HIV/AIDS education in South
Africa can not hope to succeed if it is taught as a separate area
of study, Director of the Center for the Study of AIDS at the
University of Pretoria Mary Crewe said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"What we need is to challenge our existing curricula and
integrate it (AIDS education) through all the subjects we are
teaching," she said at the African Convention of Principals here.
</P>
<P>
Crewe pointed out that South Africa has been identified as
having the fastest-growing epidemic in the world with one in 10
adults between the ages of 15 and 49 already living with the HIV
virus.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that the infection rate of South Africa's
teachers is well over 10 percent and nearly 25 percent of the
country's children live in homes or communities where HIV/AIDS are
already prevalent.
</P>
<P>
"There is no doubt that AIDS will have dramatic unimaginable
repercussions on education and the education system in South
Africa," the scholar noted.
</P>
<P>
She further emphasized that teachers also need to be trained in
how to cope with death and dying in their training program, which
should be offered by schools as a crucial part of in-service
training, and applicants for teaching positions who are not AIDS
literate should not be considered for appointment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
