<DOCNO> XIE20000823.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drought Hits Blow to Kenya's Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The new forecast is contained in a memorandum by the Treasury
to a visiting International Monetary Fund (IMF) mission which
arrived here on Wednesday to assess the impact of drought on this
year's budget.
</P>
<P>
The Gross Domestic Product growth forecast by the government
assumes that the short rains would fall in October and November as
expected and the ongoing power rationing would ease before the end
of the year.
</P>
<P>
The forecast also assumes that the country would receive
sufficient long rains as expected from March to May next year.
</P>
<P>
Due to the prolonged drought, maize production in the country
is expected to drop by between 30 to 40 percent this year. As a
result, the Kenyan government has to import 10 million bags (90-kg
per bag) of maize and 1.8 million bags of wheat this year.
</P>
<P>
The Treasury has also projected that it will spend 29 billion
shillings (around 381 million U.S. dollars) in the drought related
matters this financial year, noting that with 16 billion shillings
(around 210 million dollars) pledge by donors this year, the
government has estimated the drought would create a deficit of 20.
3 billion shillings (about 267 million dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
