<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania, Russia Cooperate in Combating Drug Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania and Russia have
agreed to enhance cooperation in combating transnational drug-
related crimes, Tanzanian local press reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
This decision was made during a meeting here Wednesday between
Tanzanian Minister for Home Affairs Mohamed Seif Khatib and the
visiting Russian Head of Committee for Combating Transnational
Crime General Ancetoly Koulikov.
</P>
<P>
They discussed measures by the two countries to collaborate in
combating illicit drug crimes and in other areas. Khatib asked the
Russian delegation to consider the possibility of helping Tanzania
to establish centers for treating drug addicts because currently
Tanzanian drug addicts are taken to general hospitals.
</P>
<P>
Koulikov said that his country is ready to further train the
Tanzanian law enforcers in the Russian specialized police unit on
combating illicit drug trade and other cross-border crimes and
enhance information and experience exchange.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania warns that East African region has become a major
illicit drug conduit connecting America, Europe and other areas in
the world due to the introduction of better means of communication
since the late 1980's.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian police have arrested 1,897 suspects dealing with
drugs between 1990 and 1999. Meanwhile, Tanzania has incorporated
education on drug abuse in training manuals in primary and
secondary schools as part of the government strategy to combat the
vice. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
