<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda to Develop Animal Husbandry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Uganda, an east African country,
needs to double its efforts to develop animal husbandry in a bit
to raise the per capita beef consumption level of its people,
according to a study report.
</P>
<P>
An average Ugandan eats only six kilograms of beef annually,
compared with the required United Nations standard of 50 kilograms,
said the report.
</P>
<P>
The New Vision newspaper reported on Thursday that the study
report, entitled "Strengthening the Uganda Beef Producers'
Association", was carried out by Swede-Agri of Sweden and funded
by Swedish International Development Agency at a cost of over 184,
000 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The report noted that only 20 percent of the grasslands was
used for cattle rearing and called for a complete rejuvenation.
The report also recommended that a new abattoir of 20 million U.S.
dollars should be set up.
</P>
<P>
Marketing, investments, breeding and disease control education
and training should be put in place in the next 10 years, said the
report.
</P>
<P>
The report has been handed over to Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni as well as Minister of Agriculture, Animal Industry and
Fisheries Kisamba Mugerwa.
</P>
<P>
The minister asked the government to support the sector
technically and political if it is to survive, said the newspaper.
</P>
</TEXT>
