<HEADLINE> Canada Welcomes Recommendations on U.N. Peacekeeping Operations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Canada was consulted during this comprehensive peacekeeping
review and we are pleased that ideas we have been advocating for
some time have been included in the recommendations," said
Canadian Foreign Minister Lloyd Axworthy in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The minister also pledged to use Canada's seat on the U.N.
Security Council and its position as co-chair of the U.N. Special
Committee on Peacekeeping to push for prompt implementation of the
panel's recommendations.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, the panel, which was established in March
2000 by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, called in a report for
improving the efficiency and restructuring of the U.N. Department
of Peacekeeping Operations, along with its information service
unit and planning task force.
</P>
<P>
Lakhdar Brahimi, former Algerian foreign minister who chairs
the panel, described the recommendations as "the first step"
toward better U.N. missions, which will also include the creation
of an enhanced rapid deployment capacity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
